{"title_page": "Buz\u0103u", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Buz\u0103u\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map           = Buzau jud Buzau.png\n|map_caption         = Location within Buz\u0103u County\n|image_skyline       = [[File:RO_BZ_Palat_Comunal_frontal_straight_cloudy.jpg|270px]]<br>[[File:Bz_tribunal.jpg|x95px]][[File:Ansamblu_episcopie.jpg|x95px]]<br>[[File:Vila_albatros_2015.jpg|x89px]][[File:Bz_Cr\u00e2ng_Foisor.jpg|x89px]]\n|image_caption       = From top, left to right: Buz\u0103u Town Hall, City Courthouse, Bishopric complex, Albatros Villa (Marghiloman Park), Cr\u00e2ng Park.\n|official_name       = Buz\u0103u\n|image_shield        = Actual Buzau CoA.png\n|leader_name         = Constantin Toma<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party        = PSD\n|established_date    = 1431 (first official record)\n|area_total_km2      = 81.3\n|elevation_m         = 95\n|coordinates         = {{coord|45|10|N|26|49|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code         = 12xxxx\n|area_code           = (+40) x38\n|website             = {{url|http://www.primariabuzau.ro}}\n}}\n\nThe city of '''Buz\u0103u''' (formerly spelled ''Buzeu'' or ''Buz\u0115u''; {{IPA-ro|bu\u02c8z\u0259w|-|Ro-Buz\u0103u.ogg}}) is the county seat of [[Buz\u0103u County]], [[Romania]], in the historical region of [[Muntenia]]. It lies near the right bank of the [[Buz\u0103u River]], between the south-eastern curvature of the [[Carpathian Mountains]] and the lowlands of [[B\u0103r\u0103gan Plain]].\n\nBuz\u0103u is a railway hub in south-eastern Romania, where railways that link Bucharest to Moldavia and Transylvania to the Black Sea coast meet. [[DN2]], a segment of [[European route E85]] crosses the city. Buz\u0103u's proximity to trade routes helped it develop its role as a commerce hub in older days, and as an industrial centre during the 20th century.\n\nDuring the Middle Ages, Buz\u0103u was a [[market town]] and [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]] [[episcopal see]] in [[Wallachia]]. It faced a period of repeated destruction during the 17th and 18th centuries, nowadays symbolized on the city seal by the [[Phoenix (mythology)|Phoenix bird]]. In the 19th century, after the end of that era, the city began to recover. The economy underwent industrialization, Buz\u0103u became a railway hub, and public education became available. At this time, the Communal Palace, the city's landmark building, and Cr\u00e2ng Park, the main recreational area, were built. The communist regime after World War II brought forced industrialization and the tripling of the city's population. Some of the factories open at the time are still functioning within the framework of market economy.\n\nThere are no universities based in Buz\u0103u, and only a few universities from other cities have remote learning facilities here. The main educational institutions here are B.P. Hasdeu high-school (where Nobel laureate George Emil Palade studied) and Mihai Eminescu high-school. The city has a number of other secondary schools, in addition to elementary schools. The Vasile Voiculescu County Library and Buz\u0103u County Museum are based in the city. The latter also manages an ethnography exhibit in the city, as well as the Vasile Voiculescu memorial house in [[P\u00e2rscov]] and the amber exhibit at [[Col\u021bi]].\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe city is named after [[Buz\u0103u (river)|the nearby river]]. In turn, the river is mentioned under the name {{lang|el|\u039c\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b5\u03bf\u03c2}} (''Mouseos'') in a document written in Greek and dated 376 AD, recounting the martyrdom of [[Sabbas the Goth]]. Historian [[Vasile P\u00e2rvan]] thought that this name is a Greek misspelling of the Thracian word ''Bouzeos'' (by losing a ''\u03c0'' from the ''\u039c\u03c0'' group, which is pronounced like a Latin ''B''). He suggested that the name comes from the Thracian root ''Buzes'', with the addition of the  ''-eu'' suffix, a form of the Greek-Latin suffix ''-aios''.<ref>Petcu, p. 19</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Buz\u0103u}}\n[[File:Vue_de_la_ville_de_Bouzeou.jpg|left|thumb|Buz\u0103u in early 20th century]][[File:1916_-_Albert_Reich_-_Buzau,_palatul_administrativ_p55.jpg|left|thumb|German occupation troops, 1916]]The written history of the city begins with that of [[\u021aara Rom\u00e2neasc\u0103|Wallachia]]. It was certified as a market town and customs point during the reign of [[Dan II of Wallachia|Dan II]].<ref>Petcu, p. 20</ref> Archeological sites belonging to [[Gumelni\u021ba\u2013Karanovo culture|Gumelni\u021ba]] and Monteoru cultures prove the presence of human inhabitants before the Christian era.<ref name=\"mjb_men_23_24\">Buz\u0103u, mic\u0103 enciclopedie istoric\u0103, pp. 23\u201324</ref> During the Middle Ages, there was also a fortress of Buz\u0103u, but only a few passing mentions in foreign documents are kept.<ref name=\"mjb_men_23_24\" /> The market that was already flourishing in 1431, has also become an Orthodox episcopal see in the early 16th century.<ref>Petcu, p. 23</ref>\n\nIn the 17th century, an era of war and foreign invasions began, that affected the town and its surroundings. They began with [[Mihai Viteazul|Michael the Brave]]'s participation in the [[Long Turkish War]]<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|pp=120}}</ref> and ended with the [[Wallachian uprising (1821)|Wallachian uprising of 1821]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|p=35}}</ref> Natural disasters (epidemics, earthquakes) also took their toll, leading to destruction and depopulation of Buz\u0103u. However, the inhabitants always returned and rebuilt the city, which led early 18th century local authorities to use the [[Phoenix (mythology)|Phoenix bird]] on the city seal, as a symbol of rebirth.<ref>Petcu, pp. 30\u201334</ref>\n\nThe 19th century brought a time of cultural and economical development.<ref>Petcu, pp. 123\u2013124</ref> The [[Communal Palace, Buz\u0103u|Communal Palace]], the city's main landmark, was built at the time,<ref name=\"Petcu 2002 53\">{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|p=53}}</ref> after the city developed its industry and became a railway hub in the 1870s. Schools were open, such as the Theological Seminary \u00een 1836, and the B. P. Hasdeu high school in 1867,<ref name=\"Petcu 2002 53\" /> and theatre plays were produced (starting 1852):<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|pp=43\u201344}}</ref> the \"Moldavia\" theatre house was built in 1898 and used throughout the first half of the 20th century as the main concert and theatre hall, where artists such as [[George Enescu]], [[C. I. Nottara]] and [[Nae Leonard]] performed.<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|p=58}}</ref> For short periods of time, [[Ion Luca Caragiale]]<ref name=\"caseleluicaragiale\">{{cite web|title=Casele lui Caragiale|url=http://adevarul.ro/cultura/istorie/casele-caragiale-1_50ba00127c42d5a663aefcfa/index.html|publisher=Adev\u0103rul|date=30 January 2002|accessdate=12 October 2007 |language=ro|trans-title=Caragiale's houses}}</ref><ref name=\"hyperliteratura_2016-08-02\">{{Citation|title=Cel mai prost c\u00e2rciumar din Istoria Literaturii \u2013 Caragiale \u0219i ber\u0103riile sale falimentare|date=2 August 2016|url=https://hyperliteratura.ro/caragiale-berarii/|author=Cosmin Dragomir|newspaper=Hyperliteratura|accessdate=3 August 2016|trans-title=The worst barkeeper in the history of literature|language=ro|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923165750/https://hyperliteratura.ro/caragiale-berarii/|archive-date=23 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Constantin Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i]] have lived and worked here.<ref>{{Harvnb|\u0218tefan|1985|pp=58\u201361}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Romania during World War I|World War I]], Buz\u0103u came under German occupation after mid-December 1916,<ref>{{YouTube|GYY8cNXQbFg|The Mesopotamian Front Awakens \u2013 Joseph Joffre Gets Sacked I THE GREAT WAR Week 125}}, ''The Great War'' by Indy Neidell. Time index 7:44.</ref> and many inhabitants took refuge in the nearby villages or in [[Western Moldavia]]. The city resumed its development after the war. The interbellum brought about the first sport matches (association football and boxing)<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|pp=69,74}}</ref> and the \"Metalurgica\" factory,<ref name=\"Buz\u0103u p. 255\">Buz\u0103u. Mic\u0103 enciclopedie istoric\u0103, p. 255</ref> a private business that was to be later confiscated by the communists, and continues to this day as part of a joined venture.\n\nAfter [[Romania in World War II|World War II]], the industrialization of Buz\u0103u was forcefully accelerated, and its population tripled in less than 50 years; new inhabitants were brought to work in newly-built factories mainly in the South of the city.<ref name=\"primariabuzau.ro_2015-05-04\">{{Citation|title=Primaria Municipiului Buzau|date=|url=http://www.primariabuzau.ro/index.php?loc=municipiul_bz&id=59&show=1|author=|newspaper=Primariabuzau.ro|accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref> Buz\u0103u has profoundly changed its appearance, working class quarters being built instead of the old commercial streets, some historical buildings,<ref name=\"Petcu 2002 94\">{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|p=94}}</ref> such as the Moldavia Theatre, were demolished. Their cultural role was taken over by the Labor Unions' Cultural Center and then by \"Dacia\" Cinema.<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|p=90}}</ref>{{Clearleft}}\n\n=== Historical buildings ===\n{{clearright}}\n[[File:RO_BZ_Vergu_Manaila_house.jpg|left|thumb|Vergu-M\u0103n\u0103il\u0103 house is the oldest habitable building in Buz\u0103u, dating from the 1780s. Except for a few churches, it is the only building from the time of successive destructions of Buz\u0103u (17th and 18th centuries). It hosts the ethnography exhibit of the County Museum.]]\nEight historical monuments classified as having national importance exist in Buz\u0103u: the church of the Birth of Christ (1649, also known colloquially as the \"Greeks' church\" or the \"Merchants' church\") along with its belfry; the courthouse (20th century); the church of the Annunciation from the former Banu monastery (16th century); the church of the Dormition in Bro\u0219teni district, (1709, along with the belfry erected in 1914); the headquarters of the orthodox bishopric with the church of the Dormition (1649), the chapel (1841), the episcopal palace (secolul al XVII-lea), the old seminary (1838), the chancellery (19th century), gate belfry and the compound wall (18th century); the Vergu-M\u0103n\u0103il\u0103 mansion (18th century, which currently hosts the ethnography exhibit of the County Museum); Vasile Voiculescu County Library (1914); and the Communal Palace (city hall, 1899\u20131903).<ref name=\"patrimoniu.gov.ro_2015-07-132\" />\n\nOne public forum monument and twelve memorial monuments are included in the list of historical monuments in Buz\u0103u County with local importance, including the urban area of Cuza Vod\u0103 street (19th century) in the old town, [[Cr\u00e2ng park]], the Albatros Villa (that used to belong to [[Alexandru Marghiloman]]) and the park, the Jewish temple, the buildings of [[Colegiul Na\u021bional B.P. Hasdeu|B.P. Hasdeu]] and [[Mihai Eminescu National College (Buz\u0103u)|Mihai Eminescu]] high-schools, a house where [[Hortensia Papadat-Bengescu]] lived for a few years, and some of the tombs in Dumbrava cemetery, such as one that was originally decorated with the statue \"Prayer\" by [[Constantin Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i]] (nowadays replaced by a replica).<ref name=\"patrimoniu.gov.ro_2015-07-132\">{{Citation|title=List of historical monuments in Buz\u0103u|date=|url=http://patrimoniu.gov.ro/images/LMI/LMI-2010_BZ.pdf|author=|newspaper=Patrimoniu.gov.ro|accessdate=13 July 2015}}</ref>{{clearright}}\n\n==Geography==\nThe city is located in the center of the county, 100&nbsp;km north-east of [[Bucure\u0219ti|Bucharest]], in the South-East of Romania, taking up a total area of 81,3&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>, at the outermost curvature of the Subcarpathian foothills, at the crossroads of the three main Romanian historical provinces: [[Wallachia]], [[Transylvania]] and [[Moldavia]]. It is entirely placed on the right bank of [[Buz\u0103u (river)|Buz\u0103u river]], which forms its northern limit. The shape of the city is oblong, longer along the river and shorter across. It reaches altitudes of 101 meters in the North-West, near the foothills, going down to 88 meters on the river bank, while the average altitude of 95 meters is the same as the altitude of Dacia square, in the city center.<ref name=\"relief2\">Petcu, pp. 102\u2013103</ref> Thus, Buz\u0103u is placed in a flat area, with a height difference of just 10 meters along a 4 kilometer line.<ref name=\"relief2\" />\n\n{{wide image|RO BZ panorama of Buzau from DN2B.jpg|1200px|Panoramic view of the west side of Buz\u0103u seen from [[Coste\u0219ti, Buz\u0103u|Sp\u0103taru]], on national road [[DN2B]]. The Curvature Subcarpathians are noticeable at the left. Main landmarks seen, starting from the left: the Ursus brewery at the edge of Simileasca district, apartment buildings of Micro 14 district, [[Cr\u00e2ng park|Cr\u00e2ng park and forest]], Ice Magic skating rink, [[Stadionul Municipal, Buz\u0103u|the City Stadium]], Micro 12/Independen\u021bei district}}\n\n=== Waterways ===\n[[Buz\u0103u (river)|Buz\u0103u river]] is the northern limit of the city. This river has created an underground basin that it permanently fuels with water.<ref>Strategia Buz\u0103u 2014\u20132020, p. 15</ref> These underground waters are a main source of drinking water, and their excess overflows to a marshy wetland south of the city, in the neighboring communes [[Coste\u0219ti, Buz\u0103u|Coste\u0219ti]], [[St\u00e2lpu]] and [[\u021ainte\u0219ti]], with small but steady [[River source|springs]], that ultimately form the [[C\u0103lm\u0103\u021bui River (Br\u0103ila)|C\u0103lm\u0103\u021bui river]].<ref>Planul Urbanistic General, pagina 6</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nAnnual rainfall is circa 500&nbsp;mm<ref name=\"clima2\">Petcu, pp.104\u2013105</ref> and in winter the snow cover can be as high as 30&nbsp;cm.<ref name=\"clima2\" /> Buz\u0103u river has a fluctuating flow. Especially in spring, when it collects melted snow from the mountain area, its level rises. The city was, however, built away from its deep and wide valley, so the river never floods the city. Even at the major floods of 2005, the waters caused no problem in the city proper, but it seriously damaged both bridges across it located in the city,<ref name=\"jurnalul2005-05-10\">{{Citation|title=Podul de la Maracineni \u2013 Moldova, rupta de Muntenia|date=10 May 2005|url=http://jurnalul.ro/stiri/observator/podul-de-la-maracineni-moldova-rupta-de-muntenia-45374.html|author=Costisitor. Circulatia A Fost Deviata Pe Rute Ocolitoare|newspaper=Jurnalul Na\u021bional|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref> which is also protected by levees, and by the small C\u00e2nde\u0219ti dam, north-west of Buz\u0103u.<ref>Planul Urbanistic General, Raportul de Mediu, partea I, pp. 24&#x2013;25</ref> The local authorities consider, however, that their strategy of defense against flood does not adequately cover the city's belt road, part of [[DN2]], which follows the river for a short stretch.<ref>Strategia Buzau 2014\u20132020, pp 25&#x2013;26, 31</ref>\n\nThe climate is [[Humid continental climate|humid continental]], with an average 92&nbsp;freezing days a year (16 with temperatures below \u221210&nbsp;\u00b0C), but also with 92&nbsp;days of hot summer.<ref name=\"clima2\" /> Local winds include the [[Criv\u0103\u021b (v\u00e2nt)|Criv\u0103\u021b]], a cold north-easterly and sometimes easterly wind in winter, and the [[Austru]], a south-westerly wind that brings dry air in summer and leads to warmer days in winter.<ref>Jude\u021bele Rom\u00e2niei Socialiste, p. 161</ref>\n\nAverage, minimum and maximum temperatures, recorded until 2006, are present in the table below. In recent years, the average temperature of July went significantly higher than 22&nbsp;\u00b0C,<ref name=\"Meteoromania.ro_2017-10-19\">{{Citation|title=Average temperatures in July 2017 in Romania|date=|url=http://www.meteoromania.ro/images/anm_maps/temperature_07_2017.png|author=National Meteorological Administration of Romania|newspaper=Meteoromania.ro|accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref> which pushes Buz\u0103u from the [[Humid continental climate|Dfb/Dfa limit to inside the Dfa zone]] in the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] (see also [[Climate of Romania]]).<ref name=\"bio-conferences.org_2017-10-19\">{{Citation|title=Modifications in climate suitability for wine production of Romanian wine regions as a result of climate change|date=4 July 2017|url=https://www.bio-conferences.org/articles/bioconf/full_html/2017/02/bioconf-oiv2017_01026/bioconf-oiv2017_01026.html#R11|author=Liviu Mihai Irimia, Cristian Valeriu Patriche, Bogdan Ro\u015fca and Valeriu V. Cotea|accessdate=19 October 2017}}; data and further sources cited by this paper.</ref>\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"margin: 0 1em 0 1em; text-align:center\" width=\"90%\"\n! colspan=\"14\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#ccccff;\" |'''Average temperatures (monthly, per year)'''*\n|- style=\"background:#DCDCDC\"\n!Perioada\n!Jan\n!Feb\n!Mar\n!Apr\n!May\n!Jun\n!Jul\n!Aug\n!Sep\n!Oct\n!Nov\n!Dec\n!All year\n|-\n|1901\u20132000\n| \u22122,2\u00b0\n| \u22120,2\u00b0\n|4,4\u00b0\n|10,9\u00b0\n|15,9\u00b0\n|19,4\u00b0\n|21,4\u00b0\n|21,9\u00b0\n|17,4\u00b0\n|11,2\u00b0\n|5,1\u00b0\n|0,4\u00b0\n|10,7\u00b0\n|-\n|2005\n|1,7\u00b0\n| \u22121,3\u00b0\n|4,1\u00b0\n|10,6\u00b0\n|17,4\u00b0\n|19,0\u00b0\n|22,4\u00b0\n|22,0\u00b0\n|18,3\u00b0\n|11,9\u00b0\n|4,8\u00b0\n|1,6\u00b0\n|11,0\u00b0\n|-\n! colspan=\"14\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#ccccff;\" |'''Minimum and maximum temperatures per month during 1901\u20132000'''\n|- style=\"background:#DCDCDC\"\n|Year\n|1936\n|1990\n|1947\n|1909;1947\n|1950\n|1908\n|'''2000'''\n|1951\n|1946\n|1952\n|1963\n|1989\n|\n|-\n|'''Maximum'''\n|18,4\u00b0\n|22,2\u00b0\n|27,9\u00b0\n|31,5\u00b0\n|37,3\u00b0\n|38,5\u00b0\n|'''39,8\u00b0'''\n|39,7\u00b0\n|37,0\u00b0\n|35,3\u00b0\n|25,0\u00b0\n|21,6\u00b0\n|\n|- style=\"background:#DCDCDC\"\n|Year\n|'''1942'''\n|1929\n|1901\n|1944\n|1915\n|1973\n|1902\n|1939\n|1977\n|1988\n|1975\n|1902\n|\n|-\n|'''Minimum'''\n|'''-29,6\u00b0'''\n| \u221225,0\u00b0\n| \u221217,0\u00b0\n| \u22125,3\u00b0\n| \u22122,0\u00b0\n|4,6\u00b0\n|7,5\u00b0\n|5,4\u00b0\n| \u22122,0\u00b0\n| \u22128,0\u00b0\n| \u221217,6\u00b0\n| \u221223,0\u00b0\n|}\n<div style=\"text-align:center\"><small>''*Statistical Yearbook of Romania, 2006''</small></div>\n\n===Flora and fauna===\n[[File:RO_BZ_Buzau_Crang_east_island_1.jpg|right|thumb|Cr\u00e2ng park, the main green area]]\nThe flora of Buz\u0103u is more diverse in the western forest of Cr\u00e2ng, 189 ha of [[oak]] forest, a remainder of the ancient [[Codrii Vl\u0103siei]].  [[Cr\u00e2ng park|The Cr\u00e2ng park itself]] takes up 10 hectares of this forest and makes up the main green area of Buz\u0103u. It is not designated as a protected area itself, but a few species of plants are protected inside it, such as the ''[[fritillaria meleagris]]'' and ''[[iris brandzae]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.anpm.ro/anpm_resources/migrated_content/files/APM%20Buzau/Biodiversitate/Cadru%20general/3FlorajudetuluiBuzau.doc|title=Flora jude\u021bului Buz\u0103u|publisher=[[Agen\u021bia Na\u021bional\u0103 pentru Protec\u021bia Mediului|ANPM]]|accessdate=2015-04-28|trans-title=Flora of Buz\u0103u County|language=ro}}</ref> In the neighboring communes of [[\u021ainte\u0219ti]] and [[Coste\u0219ti, Buz\u0103u|Coste\u0219ti]] there are other remainders of Codrii Vl\u0103siei{{mdash}} Frasinu and Sp\u0103taru forests, respectively. In the yard of the building at the intersection of Crizantemelor and Tudor Vladimirescu streets, across the street from the park in front of B. P. Hasdeu high school and the Banu church, there is a century-old [[oak]], locally protected as a monument of nature.<ref>Strategia Buz\u0103u 2014\u20132020, p. 45</ref> 6% of the [[Lunca Buz\u0103ului]] protected area, a Natura 2000 site managed by the Ecological University of Bucharest, lies within city limits, in the north and east.<ref name=\"natura2000.mmediu.ro_2015-06-02\">{{Citation|title=Lunca Buz\u0103ului|date=|url=http://natura2000.mmediu.ro/site/93/rosci0103.html|author=|newspaper=Natura2000.mmediu.ro|accessdate=2 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150112210555/http://natura2000.mmediu.ro/site/93/rosci0103.html|archive-date=12 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMost of the streets in Buz\u0103u have trees planted alongside, [[chestnut]] on Nicolae B\u0103lcescu boulevard and [[Tilia|linden]] on Unirii boulevard. In their gardens, the locals grow [[rose]]s, [[Hyacinthus orientalis|hyacinths]], [[tulip]]s, local [[Paeonia peregrina|peonies]], and [[petunia]], as well as [[Vitis|grapevines]] and [[Parthenocissus quinquefolia|Virginia creepers]] for shade. The wild fauna in Buz\u0103u is made up of city-dwelling species. The [[house sparrow]] and the [[Eurasian collared dove|collared dove]] are ubiquitous, and the most present small mammals are the [[European polecat|wild polecat]] and the [[brown rat]]. Lakes are populated with small fish, such as [[European bitterling|bitterlings]] and [[eel]], as well as [[snail]]s and [[Balkan green lizard|green lizards]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|pp=106\u2013108}}</ref>\n\nDuring the migration season, a parliament of [[short-eared owl]]s has made a habit of spending a few days in some tall fir trees located in the yard of the Forestry Inspector's Office in the city center.<ref name=\"adev2015-04-30\">{{Citation|title=VIDEO Revenirea bufni\u021belor \u00een centrul Buz\u0103ului, semn al prim\u0103verii timpurii|date=24 February 2015|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/buzau/video-revenirea-bufnitelor-centrul-buzaului-semn-primaverii-timpurii-1_54ec6ffe448e03c0fdf0fcd2/index.html|author=Iulian Bunila|newspaper=Adev\u0103rul|accessdate=30 April 2015|trans-title=The arrival of owls in downtown Buz\u0103u, a sign of early spring|language=ro}}</ref> Experimental crops from the city's Research and Development Station for [[Olericulture]] sometimes attract [[Carpathian boar|wild boars]] from the riverside forests.<ref name=\"adev2017-06-20\">{{Citation|title=VIDEO Turm\u0103 de mistre\u0163i, la doar un kilometru distan\u0163\u0103 de centrul Buz\u0103ului|date=20 June 2017|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/buzau/video-turma-porci-mistreti-mai-putin-kilometru-centrul-buzaului-1_59492e5b5ab6550cb853d73c/index.html|author=Iulian Bunila|newspaper=Adev\u0103rul|accessdate=19 October 2017|trans-title=A sounder of boars, only a kilometer away from the center of Buz\u0103u|language=ro}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n<div style=\"float:left\">{{Pie chart|thumb=left|caption=Ethnic composition of Buz\u0103u|label1=Romanians|value1=88.42|color1=#8080ff|label2=Roma|value2=4.73|color2=#80ffff|label3=Unknown|value3=6.69|color3=#9f9f9f|label4=Others|value4=0.14|color4=#555555}}{{Pie chart|thumb=left|style=clear:none;|caption=Religious composition of Buz\u0103u|label1=Orthodox Christians|value1=91.98|color1=#8080ff|label2=Unknown|value2=6.74|color2=#c0c0c0|label3=Other religions|value3=1.27|color3=#9f9f9f}}</div>According to the 2011 census, the city has {{formatnum:115494}} inhabitants, a decrease from the previous census, in 2002, when {{formatnum:134227}}&nbsp;had been recorded.<ref name=\"kia.hu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kia.hu/konyvtar/erdely/erd2002/etnii2002.zip|title=Recens\u0103m\u00e2ntul Popula\u021biei \u0219i al Locuin\u021belor 2002 \u2013 popula\u021bia unit\u0103\u021bilor administrative pe etnii|publisher=Kultur\u00e1lis Innov\u00e1ci\u00f3s Alap\u00edtv\u00e1ny (KIA.hu \u2013 Funda\u021bia Cultural\u0103 pentru Inova\u021bie)|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Most inhabitants are [[Romanians]] (88.43%), with a [[Romani people in Romania|Roma]] minority (4.73%). Ethnic affiliation is unknown for 6.69% of the population.<ref name=\"insse_2011_nat\">Rezultatele finale ale Recens\u0103m\u00e2ntului din 2011: {{Cite web|url=http://www.recensamantromania.ro/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sR_Tab_8.xls|title=Tab8. Popula\u021bia stabil\u0103 dup\u0103 etnie \u2013 jude\u021be, municipii, ora\u0219e, comune|publisher=[[Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103]] din Rom\u00e2nia|accessdate=5 August 2013 |date=July 2013}}</ref> Most inhabitants practice [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christianity]] (91.98%). Religious affiliation is unknown for 6.75% of the population.<ref name=\"insse_2011_rel\">Rezultatele finale ale Recens\u0103m\u00e2ntului din 2011: {{Cite web|url=http://www.recensamantromania.ro/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sR_TAB_13.xls|title=Tab13. Popula\u021bia stabil\u0103 dup\u0103 religie \u2013 jude\u021be, municipii, ora\u0219e, comune|publisher=[[Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103]] din Rom\u00e2nia|accessdate=5 August 2013 |date=July 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Ethnic communities ===\nThe main ethnic minority in the city are the [[Romani people of Romania|Roma]]. Throughout history, other communities have existed in Buz\u0103u, but nowadays they are nearly extinct. Those that left their mark the most on the city were the [[History of the Jews in Romania|Jewish people]] and the [[Bulgarians in Romania|Bulgarians]].\n\n==== Roma ====\nSettled after the 16th century by the Orthodox bishopric on its estate located north-west of the market town of Buz\u0103u, in Simileasca and Iorguleasca villages, Roma people have lived as [[Slavery in Romania|slaves]] who worked on the bishopric's land.<ref name=\"Lahovari_Sim\">{{cite book|title=Simileasca (Iorguleasca), com. rur.|volume=5|page=389}}</ref> After they were freed in the 19th century and, with the union between Wallachia and Moldavia, the new country got a new territorial division, Simileasca became a commune. In 1968, this commune was dissolved and integrated with Buz\u0103u. The Roma community is still located mostly in this part of the city, and it preserves its identity, although its leaders believe that Roma people in other parts of the city, who no longer speak their people's language, accept assimilation by the majority Romanians, and declare themselves Romanian at the census.<ref name=\"stradadebuzau.ro_2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=\u021aiganii din Simileasca n-au nicio jen\u0103 s\u0103-\u0219i declare etnia \u2013 Strada de Buzau|date=|url=http://www.stradadebuzau.ro/tiganii-din-simileasca-n-au-nicio-jena-sa-si-declare-etnia/|author=Corina R\u0103chi\u021beanu|newspaper=Stradadebuzau.ro|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> The community is faced with endemic poverty, high illiteracy, lack of professional qualifications and high school dropout rates, which all expose it to permanently being manipulated by politicians for elections.<ref name=\"jurnalul2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=Tiganii din Simileasca asteapta Marea Chefuiala|date=24 May 2004|url=http://jurnalul.ro/special-jurnalul/tiganii-din-simileasca-asteapta-marea-chefuiala-68413.html|author=Tatiana Dabija|newspaper=Jurnalul Na\u021bional|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> Many Roma people went abroad, especially in the countries of Northern Europe.<ref name=\"adev2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=Norvegienii finan\u021beaz\u0103 proiecte de \u00eembun\u0103t\u0103\u021bire a vie\u021bii romilor din Buz\u0103u|date=7 February 2014|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/buzau/norvegienii-finanteaza-proiecte-imbunatatire-vietii-romilor-buzau-1_52f53da8c7b855ff5628bb51/index.html|author=Iulian Bunila|newspaper=Adev\u0103rul|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ziaristionline.ro_2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=\u021aiganii pe care nu-i vede Mircea Toma. \"Tiggarna\" \u2013 Cer\u0219etorii care au invadat Bor\u00e5s \u00een Suedia vin din Buz\u0103u, satul Similesca. Foto reportaj Bor\u00e5s Tidning \u0219i George Lixandru \u2013 Ziaristi Online|date=|url=http://www.ziaristionline.ro/2015/03/28/tiganii-pe-care-nu-i-vede-mircea-toma-tiggarna-cersetorii-care-au-invadat-boras-in-suedia-vin-din-buzau-satul-similesca-foto-reportaj-boras-tidning-si-george-lixandru/|author=George Lixandru|newspaper=Ziaristionline.ro|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> The municipality also runs programs to improve theirs status, and School no. 14, located in Simileasca, is the main focus of these actions.<ref name=\"ziaristionline.ro_2015-04-28\" /> Pupils of this school publish a bilingual school newspaper, in [[Romani language|Romani]] and [[Romanian language|Romanian]], which promotes Roma integration into society.<ref name=\"opiniabuzau.ro_2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=Fiica regelui Cioab\u0103, cooptat\u0103 \u00een editarea revistei bilingve pentru romii din Simileasca|date=|url=http://opiniabuzau.ro/fiica-regelui-cioaba-cooptata-in-editarea-revistei-bilingve-pentru-romii-din-simileasca|author=Silvia Herghelegiu|newspaper=Opinia|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Jews ====\n[[File:RO_BZ_Jewish_temple_2.jpg|right|thumb|The Jewish synagogue in Buz\u0103u]]\nAlthough mentioned in documents as early as the 16th century, the [[Jews]] of Buz\u0103u became an especially important community starting with the cultural and economical development period of the 19th century. A large proportion of them were merchants and craftsmen. The Jewish cemetery appeared in 1853 and a temple dates from 1885. Between the two World Wars, 10% of the population of Buz\u0103u was Jewish,<ref name=\"adev2013-04-11\">{{Citation|title=VIDEO Cimitirul evreiesc din Buz\u0103u, un ansamblu monumental ruinat de trecera timpului \u0219i nep\u0103sarea oamenilor|date=11 April 2013|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/buzau/buzau-cimitir-evrei-1_5166524600f5182b85a74909/index.html|author=Iulian Bunila|newspaper=Adev\u0103rul|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> a large percentage compared to other cities in Wallachia, but significantly smaller than those in Moldavia, which saved the community from the brunt of the [[Ion Antonescu#Antonescu and the Holocaust|repression by Antonescu's government]]. Still, during [[World War II]], the Jews had to endure some persecutions: obligated to do compulsory work (authorities abused of the law, and extended the age of the people who had to do this work, as well as the body of the work itself), and to pay 15 million lei (four times the tax) for \"The Reunification Loan\"; certain types of objects were confiscated from them and special restrictions were imposed. The community had to host orphans whose parents had died in [[Holocaust|the Holocaust]], before they were deported to [[Transnistria Governorate|Transnistria]].<ref name=\"doctorat_maracineanu\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.unibuc.ro/studies/Doctorate2013Mai/MARACINEANU%20LAURA%20-%20COMUNITATEA%20EVREIASCA%20DE%20LA%20BUZAU%20IN%20TIMPUL%20CELUI%20DE%20AL%20DOILEA%20RAZBOI%20MONDIAL/rezumat%20maracineanu.doc|title=Comunitatea evreiasc\u0103 de la Buz\u0103u \u00een timpul celui de al Doilea R\u0103zboi Mondial|first1=Mirela-Laura|last1=M\u0103r\u0103cineanu|first2=Ion (coordonator)|last2=Bulei|publisher=Facultatea de Istorie, [[Universitatea din Bucure\u0219ti]]|year=2012}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (rezumat)</ref> During these persecutions, the Jewish community was defended by captains Stroie and Ionescu, by the Sc\u00e2nteie and Stahu families,<ref name=\"romanianjewish.org_2015-04-28\" /> and by [[Anghel Anu\u021boiu]] from Vrancea, a man who informed members of the community of upcoming Nazi raids, saving many lives, including that of Rabbi Simon Bercovich, whom he aided to leave the city and go into hiding.<ref name=\"evz2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=Lista lui b\u0103di\u021ba Anghel, salvatorul de evrei|date=11 January 2008|url=http://www.evz.ro/lista-lui-badita-anghel-salvatorul-de-evrei-2886.html|author=|newspaper=Evenimentul zilei|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://db.yadvashem.org/righteous/family.html?language=en&itemId=4044236|title=Anu\u021boiu, Anghel T.|publisher=Yad Vashem, baza de date a drep\u021bilor \u00eentre popoare|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref> After the war, most Jews of the city moved to [[Israel]], and left behind a Jewish community of only a few tens of people. Some of the personalities of the Jewish community in Buz\u0103u were painter [[Margareta Sterian]] and philosopher [[Ludwig Grunberg]].<ref name=\"romanianjewish.org_2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=Obstea evreiasca buzoiana|date=|url=http://romanianjewish.org/ro/?page_id=737#i8|author=|newspaper=Romanianjewish.org|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Bulgarians (\"Serbs\") ====\nIn the 18th century, to avoid [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] repression against Christians in the Balkans, groups of Bulgarians settled in [[\u021aara Rom\u00e2neasc\u0103|Wallachia]] where they enjoyed freedom to practice Christianity; some of these groups came to Buz\u0103u. The locals called them \"Serbs\" as a generic term for South-Slavs. The new immigrants soon started developing [[Olericulture|vegetable gardens]] as their houses were in the vicinity of the river that provided them with plenty of water, while local farmers were focusing more on raising livestock and growing cereals. Although the Bulgarian community was in time assimilated by the Romanians, to this day locals use the word \"Serb\" as a synonym to \"one who grows vegetables\".<ref name=\"bulgari\">{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|pp=27\u201334}}</ref>\n\n== Government ==\nBuz\u0103u is administered by a mayor and a local council made up of 23 councillors. The mayor, Constantin Toma, of the [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party (PSD)]], has been in office since 2016.<ref name=\"hotnews.ro_2016-10-27\">{{Citation | url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-politic-21056696-rezultate-alegeri-locale-2016-buzau-constantin-toma-psd.htm| title=Industriasul Constantin Toma (PSD) a castigat primaria Buzau \u2013 Politic| newspaper=HotNews.ro| date= 6 June 2016| author=Red. Stiri| accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> Beginning with the 2016 local elections, the local council has the following political makeup:<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/Export_mandate-2.xlsx|format=XLSX|title=Lista competitorilor care au ob\u021binut mandate|trans-title=List of candidates that obtained mandates|publisher=Biroul Electoral Central pentru alegerile locale din 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Party\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Seats\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" colspan=\"12\" | Current Council\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party (PSD)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''11'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party (PNL)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''5'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| [[People's Movement Party|People's Movement Party (PMP)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (Romania)|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (ALDE)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}}| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#ac211a\" | &nbsp;\n| [[Romanian Social Party|Romanian Social Party (PSRo)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| bgcolor=\"#ac211a\" | &nbsp;\n| bgcolor=\"#ac211a\" | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#aaa\" | &nbsp;\n| Independent\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''1'''\n| bgcolor=\"#aaa\" | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|}\nBuz\u0103u is not subdivided into any lower units, but local authorities guide their projects and strategies according to an informal division by districts. In ''Strategia 2014\u20132020'', a strategical document of the mayor's office, the following districts of Buz\u0103u were identified: Center, Micro 12/Indepeneden\u021bei, Marghiloman, Doroban\u021bi, Nicolae B\u0103lcescu, Simileasca, Micro 14, Po\u0219t\u0103, Mihai Viteazul, Pod Horticolei, Luceaf\u0103rul, Bro\u0219teni and the Industrial Zone.<ref>Strategia Buz\u0103u 2014\u20132020, pp. 87\u201398</ref>\n\nBuz\u0103u takes on the administrative role of capital of [[Buz\u0103u County]], therefore almost all county-level public services are headquartered there. Additionally, at national level, Buz\u0103u is the headquarters of the [[2nd Infantry Division (Romania)|2nd Infantry Division]] (''Getica''; former 2nd Romanian Army), one of the three divisions that make up the [[Romanian Land Forces]],<ref name=\"adev2015-01-27\">{{Citation | url=http://adevarul.ro/international/europa/maresalul-primit-onorul-divizia-2-infanterie-getica-1_524d38aac7b855ff56f41a74/index.html| title=Mare\u0219alul care a primit onorul la Divizia 2 Infanterie \"Getica\"| newspaper=Adev\u0103rul| date= 3 October 2013| author=Ion Petrescu| accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> as well as three battalions under its command{{mdash}} one of engineers, one of signals,<ref name=\"arhiva.gov.ro_2015-01-27\">{{Citation | url=http://arhiva.gov.ro/aniversarea-batalionului-47-comunicatii-si-informatica__l1a63269.html| title=Aniversarea Batalionului 47 Comunica\u021bii \u0219i Informatic\u0103| newspaper=Arhiva.gov.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> and one of logistics. Near the city, in the village of [[Cochirleanca|Boboc]], there is a military aviation school.\n\nThe highest court functioning in the city is the Buz\u0103u Tribunal, with authority over the entire county.<ref name=\"csm1909.ro_2015-04-21\">{{Citation | url=http://old.csm1909.ro/csm/index.php?cmd=9401| title=Prezentarea sistemului judiciar rom\u00e2n|trans-title=Presentation of the Romanian justice system|language=ro| publisher=Superior Magistrates' Council| date= | author=| accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> The jurisdiction of the Tribunal covers all the four local courts (''judec\u0103torii'') in the County, of which Buz\u0103u Local Court is in the city and takes cases related to Buz\u0103u and 34 surrounding communes, the largest jurisdiction of the four.<ref name=\"legex.ro_2015-04-21\">{{Citation | url=http://www.legex.ro/Hotararea-337-1993-4117.aspx| title=Hot\u0103r\u00e2rea 337/1993|trans-title=Resolution no. 337/1993| newspaper=Legex.ro| date= | author=Romanian Government| accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> The higher court to all these is the Court of Appeals in Ploie\u0219ti.<ref name=\"just.ro_2015-04-21\">{{Citation| url=http://www.just.ro/Sectiuni/SistemulJudiciar%C3%AEnRom%C3%A2nia/Legeaprivindorganizareajudiciar%C4%83nr3042004/tabid/275/Default.aspx| title=Legea privind organizarea judiciar\u0103 nr. 304/2004| trans-title=Judicial Organization Law no. 304/2004| publisher=Romanian Ministry of Justice| date=| author=Romanian Parliament| accessdate=21 April 2015}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn the Romanian Parliament, Buz\u0103u elects deputies on the lists associated with [[Buz\u0103u County]]. Of the seven deputies elected in 2016 on these lists, six ([[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|social-democrats]] [[Marcel Ciolacu]], [[Ionela Viorela Dobric\u0103]], [[Sorin Laz\u0103r]], [[D\u0103nu\u021b P\u0103le]], [[Nicolaie-Sebastian-Valentin Radu]]; and [[Adrian Mocanu]] from the [[People's Movement Party]]) have their office in Buz\u0103u, while only the [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|liberal]] [[Cristinel Romanescu]] has his in [[R\u00e2mnicu S\u0103rat]].<ref name=\"Camera Deputa\u021bilor_2017-04-24\">{{Citation | url=http://www.cdep.ro/pls/parlam/structura2015.de?leg=2016&par=C| title=Lista deputatilor \u2013 informatii de contact| newspaper=Camera Deputa\u021bilor| date= | author=Romanian Chamber of Deputies| accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 19th century, local statesman [[Alexandru Marghiloman]], owner of a large estate and a mansion near the city, became prominent.<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://www.opiniabuzau.ro/index.php/istorii-buzoiene/2323-radiografii-subiective-alexandru-marghiloman-lordul-valah-i|title=Radiografii subiective \u2013 Alexandru Marghiloman \u2013 lordul valah (I)|publisher=Opinia|location=Buz\u0103u|date=27 June 2011|accessdate=2013-12-06|first=Nicolae|last=Pene\u0219}}</ref> Germanofile, Marghiloman was prime minister around the end of [[World War I]], when Romania was compelled to sign the [[Treaty of Bucharest (1918)|Treaty of Bucharest]] of 1918 and began the process of integrating [[Bessarabia]], which had proclaimed its union with Romania in mid-April of that year.<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://www.historia.ro/exclusiv_web/general/articol/unirea-basarabiei-romania-documente|title=Unirea Basarabiei cu Rom\u00e2nia \u00een documente|publisher=Historia.ro|accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref> Another known contemporary politician from Buz\u0103u is [[C\u0103t\u0103lin Predoiu]]; initially, an independent Minister of Justice in the government of [[C\u0103lin Popescu-T\u0103riceanu]],<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-politic-2476877-catalin-marian-predoiu-noul-ministru-justitiei.htm|title=Catalin Marian Predoiu, noul ministru al Justitiei|author=Dumitrina Galantonu|date=29 February 2008|accessdate=2013-12-06|publisher=[[Hotnews.ro]]}}</ref> Predoiu became a member of the National Liberal Party (PNL), after which he quit in 2008 to continue as minister, and in 2013 has attempted to obtain the presidential nomination of the [[Democratic Liberal Party (Romania)|Democratic Liberal Party]] for the next year's election;<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/evenimentul-zilei-tv-invitatul-de-astazi-este-catalin-preda-1068668.html|title=Evenimentul zilei TV. C\u0103t\u0103lin Predoiu s-ar retrage din lupta pentru preziden\u021biale dac\u0103 un alt candidat de dreapta ar avea \u0219anse mai mari|publisher=[[Evenimentul Zilei]]|first=Alexandra|last=Ciliac|accessdate=2013-12-06|date=21 November 2013}}</ref> eventually, that party merged with the PNL, who nominated Klaus Iohannis, and Predoiu became shadow prime-minister.<ref name=\"evz2015-04-21\">{{Citation | url=http://www.evz.ro/vasile-blaga-catalin-predoiu-prim-ministru-desemnat-al-aliantei-noastre.html| title=Vasile Blaga: C\u0103t\u0103lin Predoiu, prim-ministru desemnat al alian\u021bei noastre| newspaper=Evenimentul zilei| date= 11 August 2014| author=Andreea Udrea| accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n\n=== Economic history ===\nDuring the Middle Ages, Buz\u0103u's economy was based on trade, as the market town began as a customs and exchange point, and developed due to its position at the curvature of the Carpathians, in a plase where roads that connected Wallachia to [[Moldova|Moldavia]] and [[Transilvania|Transylvania]] met. The old market town tradition is still preserved in the ''Dr\u0103gaica'' fair, held every June around [[Midsummer]], bringing together small producers and merchants from diverse regions of Romania.\n\nThe agricultural reform during [[Alexandru Ioan Cuza]] led some of the Bulgarian gardners to rent in 1897 \u0219i 1898 some land acquired by the state from the bishopric. The developed a distribution network for their produce both in Buz\u0103u, and in other nearby cities such as [[Bra\u0219ov]], [[Ploie\u0219ti]] or [[R\u00e2mnicu S\u0103rat]]. Their activity became even more lucrative after the land reform of 1921.<ref>Petcu, 2002, p. 134</ref>\n\nAfter the period of repeated invasions and destruction ended in the 19th century, the economy began to industrialize as well. Towards the end of that century, the development of a Romanian railway network made Buz\u0103u one of its important hubs and pushed the small craftsmen's shops to evolve into industrial installations. The first such facility was the ''Garoflid mill'', open in 1883, that worked also as a [[Textile|cloth]] factory.<ref name=\"petcu1353\">Petcu, 2002, p. 135</ref> \u00cen 1894, an [[Petrol|oil]] refinery of the ''Saturn'' society was built; this refinery was to function for 50 years.\n\nAfter a dramatic nationwide decrease caused by the [[First World War]] (the 1919 output was a quarter of the one in 1913<ref name=\"petcu1353\" />), the industrial development picked up steam during the interbellum. One of the main components of the local industry was [[Mill (grinding)|milling]]. The first industrial mill in the city, ''Garoflid'', renamed ''Zangopol'' after its new owner, had reached a capital of 5 million [[Romanian leu|lei]] in 1928 and, 30 de million in 1938, while the company that operated it had around 100 employees.<ref name=\"petcu1363\">Petcu, 2002, p. 136</ref> Another business started at this time was ''Metalurgica \u0219i Turn\u0103torie \u2013 S.A.'' (Metallurgy and Foundry), founded in 1928 with a capital of over 9 million lei. Although it had an initially difficult period, as it was closed during the [[Great Depression]], it was reopened in 1933, only to be closed again in 1940 and 1944, during World War II.<ref name=\"Buz\u0103u p. 255\" />\n[[File:1970_Intreprinderea_de_geamuri_Buzau.JPG|left|thumb|Buz\u0103u window factory in 1970]]\nAfter [[World War II]], on 11 June 1948 all factories were requisitioned by the Communist government, who also began a program of forced industrialization, even though some of the industries that were being developed were unfit to the region.<ref name=\"petcu1373\">Petcu, 2002, p. 137</ref> In 1965, the 318 [[Hectare|ha]] Buz\u0103u South industrial platform began to be built around the old location of the ''Saturn'' refinery, blown up during the war. It was the location of the city's most important factories that were developed at the time: the Steel Wire and Steel Wire Products Enterprise (after 1990, ''Ductil''), the Railway Machinery Enterprise (after 1990, ''[[VAE Apcarom|Apcarom]]''), ''Metalurgica'' (the one founded in 1928), the Glass and Windows Factory (after 1991, ''[[Gerom Buz\u0103u|Gerom S.A.]]'').\n[[File:RO_BZ_Contactoare.jpg|right|thumb|The \"Contactoare\" electrical relays factory in Buz\u0103u]]\nOther facilities were located in other parts of the city, such as the Contactors Enterprise, in the North-East, and the Plastic Works (after 1990, ''[[Romcarbon|Romcarbon S.A.]]'') in the North.\n\nDespite the forced industrialization, Buz\u0103u was spared from becoming dependent on a single industry, and there was no single point of failure for the city's economy. According to the new law of commerce of 1990, that came after the [[Romanian Revolution of 1989|fall of Communism]], these factories were organised as state-owned companies, and were privatised. Most of them survived the transition to a [[market economy]], as many of them thus became viable.\n\n=== Present economy ===\nCurrently, the largest Buz\u0103u-based company is Romet, a [[holding company]] made up of multiple firms that produse isolation materials for water and gas pipes, water filters, fire extinguishers and other related products. It was successful in the 1990s, with the ''Aquator'' home water purifier. In 1999, it also acquired ''Aromet S.A.'', the company that operated the 1928 ''Metalurgica'' factory.<ref>Petcu, p. 141</ref>\n[[File:Buzau_ductil.jpg|left|thumb|240x240px|Ductil steel wire factory]]\nOther Buz\u0103u-based companies were privatised by programs supervised by the [[World Bank]]. [[VAE Apcarom|''Apcarom S.A.'']], the only Romanian producer of railway equipments,<ref name=\"petcu1382\">Petcu, 2002, p. 138</ref> was acquired by the Austrian company VAE, and in 2008 had a capital of 7.38&nbsp;million lei.<ref name=\"curierulnational.ro_2006-07-31\">{{Citation|title=Profit in scadere pentru Apcarom|date=31 July 2006|url=http://www.curierulnational.ro/Economie/2006-07-31/Profit+in+scadere+pentru+Apcarom|author=|newspaper=Curierul Na\u021bional|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref> ''Ductil S.A.'', one of the largest companies in the city, was privatised in 1999 and divided subsequently, during 1999\u20132000 by the new majority shareholder, FRO Spa, who only kept the electrodes and welding equipment facilities, and sold out the others. The steel wire, welded metal net, concrete and iron works became [[Ductil Steel S.A.]] and passed to the Italian company Sidersipe.<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://old.standard.money.ro/articol_6897/constructiile_sporesc_afacerile_ductil_steel.html|title=Constructiile sporesc afacerile Ductil Steel|date=18 July 2007|accessdate=2008-02-22|publisher=Business Standard|archiveurl=http://www.construction-briefly.ro/articol/constructiile-sporesc-afacerile-ductil-steel|archivedate=18 July 2007}}</ref> The iron powder works became ''Ductil Iron Powder''. In 2007, FRO Spa sold ''Ductil S.A.'' to the Russian company [[Mechel]], for 90 million euro.<ref name=\"hotnews.ro_2007-10-5\">{{Citation|title=Rusii de la Mechel cumpara cu 90 mil. euro Ductil Buzau|date=5 October 2007|url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-arhiva-1020251-rusii-mechel-cumpara-90-mil-euro-ductil-buzau.htm|author=|newspaper=HotNews.ro|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref> ''Zah\u0103rul S.A.'', the town's sugar producer, was acquired by ''Agrana Rom\u00e2nia'', an Austrian-based group that also owned other sugar factories in [[Roman, Neam\u021b|Roman]], a starch factory in [[\u021a\u0103nd\u0103rei]] and a juice facility in [[Vaslui]].<ref name=\"zf.ro_2010-09-21\">{{Citation|title=Austriecii \u00eenchid fabrica de zah\u0103r de la Buz\u0103u timp de 4 luni|date=21 September 2010|url=http://www.zf.ro/companii/austriecii-inchid-fabrica-de-zahar-de-la-buzau-timp-de-4-luni-7357694|author=Diana Tudor Stoica|newspaper=Ziarul financiar|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nMilling is still present on the local market: the largest local producer is [[Boromir Prod]], controlled by businessman Constantin Boromiz,<ref name=\"zf.ro_2009-05-11\">{{Citation|title=Cum a ajuns Constantin Boromiz de la o moara in satul natal la un business de 150 de milioane de euro in panificatie|date=11 May 2009|url=http://www.zf.ro/companii/cum-a-ajuns-constantin-boromiz-de-la-o-moara-in-satul-natal-la-un-business-de-150-de-milioane-de-euro-in-panificatie-4333603/|author=Diana Tudor Stoica|newspaper=Ziarul financiar|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref> owner of the ''Boromir'' group, who also owns Boromir Ind V\u00e2lcea, Panmed [[Media\u0219]] and Comcereal [[Sibiu]].<ref name=\"zf.ro_2009-05-11\" /><ref>[http://www.wall-street.ro/tag/boromir-prod-buzau.html Scurt\u0103 prezentare \u0219i list\u0103 de \u0219tiri] asociate firmei Boromir Prod Buz\u0103u, pe website-ul [[Wall-street.ro]]. Accesat la 18 August 2015</ref>\n\nThe economy is still more oriented towards industry rather than services, which, according to a 2016 survey of the World Bank, made it more attractive to the labor force of lower qualification (at best with a high school degree). The same survey showed that most of the labor force in the city came from within the county, as Buz\u0103u is the center of a highly rural, compact and densely-populated area. The city was found to be in competition with larger cities for the labor force from other counties, a feature it shares with [[Alexandria, Romania|Alexandria]]. The proximity of Bucharest makes Buz\u0103u itself a source of internal migration, thus orbiting the capital city. Buz\u0103u is the second city (closely after [[Ploie\u0219ti]], a city with almost double the population), by the number of employees in Bucharest coming from other cities between 1991 and 2011; the survey points out that this has been a disadvantage, but might become an opportunity in the future.<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/448771499322731333/pdf/116400-ROMANIAN-REVISED-PUBLIC-Magnet-Cities-Migration-and-Commuting-in-Romania-RO.pdf|title=Ora\u0219e-magnet. Migra\u021bie \u0219i navetism \u00een Rom\u00e2nia|author=Marius Cristea, Codru\u021ba Mare, Ciprian Moldovan, Andreea China, Thomas Farole, Adina Vin\u021ban, Jane Park, Keith Patrick Garrett \u0219i Marcel Ionescu-Heroiu|publisher=[[Banca Mondial\u0103]]|accessdate=27 July 2017}}, paginile 25, 40, 65</ref>\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:RO BZ Railway station.jpg|thumb|The main railway station in Buz\u0103u]]\n[[File:Buzau BMC bus 3.jpg|thumb|City bus on route 1, near the Buz\u0103u railway station]]\n\n===Rail===\nBuz\u0103u is one of the country's main important railway hubs, as it connects [[Bucharest]] and [[Ploie\u0219ti]] with [[Foc\u0219ani]], [[Gala\u021bi]] and [[Constan\u021ba]]. The city railway station was open in 1872, along with the Bucharest-Gala\u021bi railway.<ref name=\"hotnews.ro_2014-03-14\">{{Citation | url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-esential-16807977-analiza-cum-mergeau-trenurile-acum-140-ani-poveste-romani-unguri-austrieci-englezi-vremuri-scandaluri-rasunatoare-reusite-uimitoare.htm| title=ANALIZA Cum mergeau trenurile acum 140 de ani - O poveste cu romani, unguri, austrieci si englezi in vremuri cu scandaluri rasunatoare si reusite uimitoare - Esential| newspaper=HotNews.ro| date= 2014-03-13| author=Vlad Barza| accessdate=2015-06-02}}</ref>\n\nA branch of this railway, from Buz\u0103u to M\u0103r\u0103\u0219e\u0219ti was opened a few years later, on [[13 June]] [[1881]],<ref name=\"gds.ro_2011-02-05\">{{Citation | url=http://www.gds.ro/Local/2011-02-05/Calea+ferata+din+Romania++si+inceputurile+ei/| title=Calea ferat\u0103 din Rom\u00e2nia \u0219i \u00eenceputurile ei| newspaper=Gazeta de Sud| date= 5 February 2011 | author=| accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref> and it was the first railway designed by Romanian engineers.<ref name=\"agir.ro_2015-06-02\">{{Citation | url=http://www.agir.ro/istoric.php| title=Istoric|publisher=Asociatia Generala a Inginerilor din Romania| newspaper=Agir.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=2015-06-02}}</ref>\n\nThe Buz\u0103u-Nehoia\u0219u line, open in 1908, connects Buz\u0103u to the smaller towns and villages along the [[Buz\u0103u River]] valley, including [[Nehoiu]] and [[P\u0103t\u00e2rlagele]].<ref name=\"Nicolescu_Opinia\">{{Cite news|title=Linia C.F.R. Buzau - Nehoiasu, 100 de ani de la inaugurare (august 1909)|date=30 June 2009|first=Valeriu|last=Nicolescu|first2=Monica|last2=B\u0103nic\u0103|newspaper=Opinia|location=Buz\u0103u}}, a copy of that article is available online on the [http://www.transira.ro/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=3760 Transira forum]</ref>\n\n===Road===\nBuz\u0103u is crossed by national road [[DN2]] (part of [[European Road E85]]), which connects the city to [[Bucharest]] to the South and to [[R\u00e2mnicu S\u0103rat]] and the main cities of [[Western Moldavia]] to the North. National road [[DN1B]] (European Road E577) branches out of DN2 in Buz\u0103u. This road connects the city to [[Ploie\u0219ti]]. In the North of the city, [[DN10]] also branches from DN2. It crosses the Carpathians at their South-Eastern curvature through [[Buz\u0103u Pass]] towards [[Bra\u0219ov]]. The South of Buz\u0103u is also crossed by national road DN2B, which branches from DN2 \u00een the neighboring commune of Coste\u0219ti, leading eastward to Gala\u021bi and [[Br\u0103ila]]. In Buz\u0103u, county road DJ203D branches from DN2B. It leads South to [[\u021ainte\u0219ti, Buz\u0103u|\u021ainte\u0219ti]] and [[Smeeni, Buz\u0103u|Smeeni]], where it ends in [[DN2C]], a road along which it helps connect Buz\u0103u to [[Slobozia]].<ref>{{Google maps|accessdate=2015-04-28|url=https://www.google.ro/maps/@45.1446317,26.8161519,13z}}</ref>\n\nIn the Buz\u0103u city area, the only functional road bridge over Buz\u0103u River is the one crossing with DN2 to [[M\u0103r\u0103cineni, Buz\u0103u|M\u0103r\u0103cineni]]. There is another road bridge, connecting the city to [[Vadu Pa\u0219ii, Buz\u0103u|Vadu Pa\u0219ii]], near the railway bridge. It was however closed after it was destroyed by a flash flood in 2005, and repairs kept being postponed, which had an impact on the economy of the neighboring communes, North-East of the city, as it remains used only by pedestrians and cyclists.<ref name=\"adev2015-06-02\">{{Citation | url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/buzau/maternitatea-noua-podul-vadu-pasii-principalii-agenti-electorali-buzaului-1_5475895ba0eb96501e186dde/index.html| title=Maternitatea nou\u0103 \u0219i Podul Vadu Pa\u0219ii, principalii agen\u021bi electorali ai Buz\u0103ului| newspaper=Adev\u0103rul| date= 26 November 2014| author=Iulian Bunila| accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"stiri.tvr.ro_2015-06-02\">{{Citation | url=http://stiri.tvr.ro/podul-de-la-vadu-pasii-proiectat-de-anghel-saligny-e-inchis-traficului-auto_52467.html| title=Podul de la Vadu Pa\u0219ii, proiectat de Anghel Saligny, e \u00eenchis traficului auto| newspaper=Stiri.tvr.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> Works began in the fall of 2017.<ref name=\"adev2017-09-04\">{{Citation | url=https://adevarul.ro/locale/buzau/au-inceput-lucrarile-podul-vadu-pasii-marti-interzis-accesul-pietonilor-1_59ad7a7a5ab6550cb8a0ee48/index.html| title=VIDEO Au \u00eenceput lucr\u0103rile la podul de la Vadu Pa\u015fii. De mar\u0163i, va fi interzis accesul pietonilor| newspaper=Adev\u0103rul| date= 4 September 2017| author=Iulian Bunila| accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nTwo main bust stations, one in the North and one in the South next to the railway station, as well a few other secondary bus stops, are used by private transportation companies that operate services to other cities or nearby villages.<ref name=\"autogari.ro_2015-04-28\">{{Citation | url=http://www.autogari.ro/Buzau/| title=Autogari din Buzau, Romania si curse autocare, microbuze| newspaper=Autogari.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Air===\n\nBuz\u0103u has no civil airport. The only air transport infrastructure present in the city is the military airport and heliport South-West of the city, but it is used only by emergency sanitary flights.<ref>Strategia Buz\u0103u 2014-2020, pp 53&ndash;54</ref> Civil air traffic for Buz\u0103u is performed through [[Henri Coand\u0103 International Airport]] in [[Otopeni]], 110&nbsp;km away, the main air hub for Wallachia.<ref name=\"agerpres.ro_2015-06-02\">{{Citation | url=http://www.agerpres.ro/politica/2010/12/09/boagiu-vrem-sa-transformam-aeroportul-otopeni-in-aeroport-regional-iar-baneasa-in-aeroport-business-13-05-04| title=Boagiu: Vrem s\u0103 transform\u0103m Aeroportul Otopeni \u00een aeroport regional, iar B\u0103neasa \u00een aeroport business \u2013 AGERPRES| newspaper=Agerpres.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Public transportation===\n10 bus lines connect residential areas to industrial areas (including Buz\u0103u South industrial platform), the city center and the railway station.<ref name=\"transbusbuzau.ro_2015-04-28\">{{Citation | url=http://www.transbusbuzau.ro/index.php?subj=19| title=Harti Trasee - TransBus Buzau| newspaper=Transbusbuzau.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> There are a few taxi companies licensed by the city also operating in the surrounding villages.<ref name=\"reporterbuzoian.ro_2015-08-18\">{{Citation | url=http://reporterbuzoian.ro/cate-taxiuri-tranziteaza-zilnic-municipiul-buzau/| title=C\u00e2te taxiuri tranziteaz\u0103 zilnic municipiul Buz\u0103u?| newspaper=Reporterbuzoian.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Education and culture==\n[[File:RO BZ County library.jpg|thumb|The ''Vasile Voiculescu'' memorial county library in Buz\u0103u]]\n\nThe first school in Buz\u0103u was the school for church and icon painters, opened by Chesarie, the bishop of Buz\u0103u. The school functioned at the bishopric of Buz\u0103u, and was managed by [[Nicolae Teodorescu]]. [[Gheorghe Tattarescu]] started learning painting here.\n\nThe city's most important educational landmark is the [[Bogdan Petriceicu Hasdeu National College|''Bogdan Petriceicu Hasdeu'' National College]], attended by the Nobel prize winner [[George Emil Palade]] in his youth. The ''Hasdeu'' high school was inaugurated in 1867.\n\nThe city's public library was opened in 1893, under the name of ''[[Carol I]] Public Library''. Later it took the name of [[Vasile Voiculescu]], Buz\u0103u's most prominent author, writer, and poet.\n\n[[File:Colti amber museum.jpg|thumb|right|260px|Buz\u0103u County Museum]]\n\nThe ''George Ciprian'' stage theatre was created in 1996. It does not have an acting crew of its own, relying on contracts. Its first manager was playwright [[Paul Ioachim]].\n\nThe first university in the city was the Economic University College, inaugurated in 1992, a branch of the [[Academy of Economic Studies]] in [[Bucharest]].\n\nThe main museum in Buz\u0103u is the ''Buz\u0103u County Museum'', which exhibits items related to the region's history. The same museum oversees the [[ethnography]] exhibition at the [[Vergu-M\u0103n\u0103il\u0103 House]], as well as the ''[[Amber]] Museum'' in [[Col\u021bi]] and the ''Vasile Voiculescu Memorial House'' in [[P\u00e2rscov]].\n\n==Buz\u0103u natives==\n* [[Ion B\u0103ie\u0219u]], playwright\n* [[Constantin Budeanu]], electrical engineer\n* [[Vasile C\u00e2rlova]], poet\n* [[George Ciprian]], actor, playwright\n* [[Constantin C. Giurescu]], historian\n* [[\u0218tefan Gu\u0219\u0103]], Romanian Army general\n* [[Paul Ioachim]], actor, playwright\n* [[Mico Kaufman]], sculptor\n* [[Alexandru Marghiloman]], statesman, [[Prime Minister of Romania]]\n* [[Mihaela Runceanu]], pop singer\n* [[Radu G. Vl\u0103descu]], professor at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine at the [[University of Agronomical Sciences and Veterinary Medicine]], [[Bucharest]], member of the [[Romanian Academy]] and correspondent member of the [[French Academy]]\n* [[Vasile Voiculescu]], poet, writer, playwright\n\n===Prominent mayors===\n* [[Nicu Constantinescu]]\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Stan S\u0103raru|ro}}\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Romania}}\nBuz\u0103u is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n* [[Oudenaarde]], [[Belgium]], since 1999\n* [[Agios Dimitrios]], [[Greece]], since 2006\n* [[Soroca]], [[Moldova]], since 2012\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Buz\u0103u}}\n* {{cite book | first=Gheorghe | last=Petcu|author2=Constantin Stan |author3=Doina Ciobanu |author4=Constan\u021ba T\u0103nase |author5=Doina Filoti  | title = Municipiul Buz\u0103u. Monografie | location = Buz\u0103u | publisher = Editura Alpha| year = 2002|language=Romanian | isbn = 978-973-8054-81-3}}\n* {{cite book | first=Corneliu | last=\u0218tefan | title = La noapte, Cotidianul | location = Bucharest | publisher = Editura Eminescu| year = 1985|language=Romanian}}\n\n{{Buz\u0103u County}}\n{{Cities in Romania}}\n{{RoJudCapitals}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buzau}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Buz\u0103u County]]\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Capitals of Romanian counties]]\n[[Category:Localities in Muntenia]]\n[[Category:Buz\u0103u| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Buz\u0103u\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map           = Buzau jud Buzau.png\n|map_caption         = Location within Buz\u0103u County\n|image_skyline       = [[File:RO_BZ_Palat_Comunal_frontal_straight_cloudy.jpg|270px]]<br>[[File:Bz_tribunal.jpg|x95px]][[File:Ansamblu_episcopie.jpg|x95px]]<br>[[File:Vila_albatros_2015.jpg|x89px]][[File:Bz_Cr\u00e2ng_Foisor.jpg|x89px]]\n|image_caption       = From top, left to right: Buz\u0103u Town Hall, City Courthouse, Bishopric complex, Albatros Villa (Marghiloman Park), Cr\u00e2ng Park.\n|official_name       = Buz\u0103u\n|image_shield        = Actual Buzau CoA.png\n|leader_name         = Constantin Toma\n|leader_party        = PSD\n|established_date    = 1431 (first official record)\n|area_total_km2      = 81.3\n|elevation_m         = 95\n|coordinates         = {{coord|45|10|N|26|49|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code         = 12xxxx\n|area_code           = (+40) x38\n|website             = {{url|http://www.primariabuzau.ro}}\n}}\n\nThe city of '''Buz\u0103u''' (formerly spelled ''Buzeu'' or ''Buz\u0115u''; {{IPA-ro|bu\u02c8z\u0259w|-|Ro-Buz\u0103u.ogg}}) is the county seat of [[Buz\u0103u County]], [[Romania]], in the historical region of [[Muntenia]]. It lies near the right bank of the [[Buz\u0103u River]], between the south-eastern curvature of the [[Carpathian Mountains]] and the lowlands of [[B\u0103r\u0103gan Plain]].\n\nBuz\u0103u is a railway hub in south-eastern Romania, where railways that link Bucharest to Moldavia and Transylvania to the Black Sea coast meet. [[DN2]], a segment of [[European route E85]] crosses the city. Buz\u0103u's proximity to trade routes helped it develop its role as a commerce hub in older days, and as an industrial centre during the 20th century.\n\nDuring the Middle Ages, Buz\u0103u was a [[market town]] and [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]] [[episcopal see]] in [[Wallachia]]. It faced a period of repeated destruction during the 17th and 18th centuries, nowadays symbolized on the city seal by the [[Phoenix (mythology)|Phoenix bird]]. In the 19th century, after the end of that era, the city began to recover. The economy underwent industrialization, Buz\u0103u became a railway hub, and public education became available. At this time, the Communal Palace, the city's landmark building, and Cr\u00e2ng Park, the main recreational area, were built. The communist regime after World War II brought forced industrialization and the tripling of the city's population. Some of the factories open at the time are still functioning within the framework of market economy.\n\nThere are no universities based in Buz\u0103u, and only a few universities from other cities have remote learning facilities here. The main educational institutions here are B.P. Hasdeu high-school (where Nobel laureate George Emil Palade studied) and Mihai Eminescu high-school. The city has a number of other secondary schools, in addition to elementary schools. The Vasile Voiculescu County Library and Buz\u0103u County Museum are based in the city. The latter also manages an ethnography exhibit in the city, as well as the Vasile Voiculescu memorial house in [[P\u00e2rscov]] and the amber exhibit at [[Col\u021bi]].\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe city is named after [[Buz\u0103u (river)|the nearby river]]. In turn, the river is mentioned under the name {{lang|el|\u039c\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b5\u03bf\u03c2}} (''Mouseos'') in a document written in Greek and dated 376 AD, recounting the martyrdom of [[Sabbas the Goth]]. Historian [[Vasile P\u00e2rvan]] thought that this name is a Greek misspelling of the Thracian word ''Bouzeos'' (by losing a ''\u03c0'' from the ''\u039c\u03c0'' group, which is pronounced like a Latin ''B''). He suggested that the name comes from the Thracian root ''Buzes'', with the addition of the  ''-eu'' suffix, a form of the Greek-Latin suffix ''-aios''.<ref>Petcu, p. 19</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Buz\u0103u}}\n[[File:Vue_de_la_ville_de_Bouzeou.jpg|left|thumb|Buz\u0103u in early 20th century]][[File:1916_-_Albert_Reich_-_Buzau,_palatul_administrativ_p55.jpg|left|thumb|German occupation troops, 1916]]The written history of the city begins with that of [[\u021aara Rom\u00e2neasc\u0103|Wallachia]]. It was certified as a market town and customs point during the reign of [[Dan II of Wallachia|Dan II]].<ref>Petcu, p. 20</ref> Archeological sites belonging to [[Gumelni\u021ba\u2013Karanovo culture|Gumelni\u021ba]] and Monteoru cultures prove the presence of human inhabitants before the Christian era.<ref name=\"mjb_men_23_24\">Buz\u0103u, mic\u0103 enciclopedie istoric\u0103, pp. 23\u201324</ref> During the Middle Ages, there was also a fortress of Buz\u0103u, but only a few passing mentions in foreign documents are kept.<ref name=\"mjb_men_23_24\" /> The market that was already flourishing in 1431, has also become an Orthodox episcopal see in the early 16th century.<ref>Petcu, p. 23</ref>\n\nIn the 17th century, an era of war and foreign invasions began, that affected the town and its surroundings. They began with [[Mihai Viteazul|Michael the Brave]]'s participation in the [[Long Turkish War]]<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|pp=120}}</ref> and ended with the [[Wallachian uprising (1821)|Wallachian uprising of 1821]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|p=35}}</ref> Natural disasters (epidemics, earthquakes) also took their toll, leading to destruction and depopulation of Buz\u0103u. However, the inhabitants always returned and rebuilt the city, which led early 18th century local authorities to use the [[Phoenix (mythology)|Phoenix bird]] on the city seal, as a symbol of rebirth.<ref>Petcu, pp. 30\u201334</ref>\n\nThe 19th century brought a time of cultural and economical development.<ref>Petcu, pp. 123\u2013124</ref> The [[Communal Palace, Buz\u0103u|Communal Palace]], the city's main landmark, was built at the time,<ref name=\"Petcu 2002 53\">{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|p=53}}</ref> after the city developed its industry and became a railway hub in the 1870s. Schools were open, such as the Theological Seminary \u00een 1836, and the B. P. Hasdeu high school in 1867,<ref name=\"Petcu 2002 53\" /> and theatre plays were produced (starting 1852):<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|pp=43\u201344}}</ref> the \"Moldavia\" theatre house was built in 1898 and used throughout the first half of the 20th century as the main concert and theatre hall, where artists such as [[George Enescu]], [[C. I. Nottara]] and [[Nae Leonard]] performed.<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|p=58}}</ref> For short periods of time, [[Ion Luca Caragiale]]<ref name=\"caseleluicaragiale\">{{cite web|title=Casele lui Caragiale|url=http://adevarul.ro/cultura/istorie/casele-caragiale-1_50ba00127c42d5a663aefcfa/index.html|publisher=Adev\u0103rul|date=30 January 2002|accessdate=12 October 2007 |language=ro|trans-title=Caragiale's houses}}</ref><ref name=\"hyperliteratura_2016-08-02\">{{Citation|title=Cel mai prost c\u00e2rciumar din Istoria Literaturii \u2013 Caragiale \u0219i ber\u0103riile sale falimentare|date=2 August 2016|url=https://hyperliteratura.ro/caragiale-berarii/|author=Cosmin Dragomir|newspaper=Hyperliteratura|accessdate=3 August 2016|trans-title=The worst barkeeper in the history of literature|language=ro|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923165750/https://hyperliteratura.ro/caragiale-berarii/|archive-date=23 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Constantin Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i]] have lived and worked here.<ref>{{Harvnb|\u0218tefan|1985|pp=58\u201361}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Romania during World War I|World War I]], Buz\u0103u came under German occupation after mid-December 1916,<ref>{{YouTube|GYY8cNXQbFg|The Mesopotamian Front Awakens \u2013 Joseph Joffre Gets Sacked I THE GREAT WAR Week 125}}, ''The Great War'' by Indy Neidell. Time index 7:44.</ref> and many inhabitants took refuge in the nearby villages or in [[Western Moldavia]]. The city resumed its development after the war. The interbellum brought about the first sport matches (association football and boxing)<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|pp=69,74}}</ref> and the \"Metalurgica\" factory,<ref name=\"Buz\u0103u p. 255\">Buz\u0103u. Mic\u0103 enciclopedie istoric\u0103, p. 255</ref> a private business that was to be later confiscated by the communists, and continues to this day as part of a joined venture.\n\nAfter [[Romania in World War II|World War II]], the industrialization of Buz\u0103u was forcefully accelerated, and its population tripled in less than 50 years; new inhabitants were brought to work in newly-built factories mainly in the South of the city.<ref name=\"primariabuzau.ro_2015-05-04\">{{Citation|title=Primaria Municipiului Buzau|date=|url=http://www.primariabuzau.ro/index.php?loc=municipiul_bz&id=59&show=1|author=|newspaper=Primariabuzau.ro|accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref> Buz\u0103u has profoundly changed its appearance, working class quarters being built instead of the old commercial streets, some historical buildings,<ref name=\"Petcu 2002 94\">{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|p=94}}</ref> such as the Moldavia Theatre, were demolished. Their cultural role was taken over by the Labor Unions' Cultural Center and then by \"Dacia\" Cinema.<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|p=90}}</ref>{{Clearleft}}\n\n=== Historical buildings ===\n{{clearright}}\n[[File:RO_BZ_Vergu_Manaila_house.jpg|left|thumb|Vergu-M\u0103n\u0103il\u0103 house is the oldest habitable building in Buz\u0103u, dating from the 1780s. Except for a few churches, it is the only building from the time of successive destructions of Buz\u0103u (17th and 18th centuries). It hosts the ethnography exhibit of the County Museum.]]\nEight historical monuments classified as having national importance exist in Buz\u0103u: the church of the Birth of Christ (1649, also known colloquially as the \"Greeks' church\" or the \"Merchants' church\") along with its belfry; the courthouse (20th century); the church of the Annunciation from the former Banu monastery (16th century); the church of the Dormition in Bro\u0219teni district, (1709, along with the belfry erected in 1914); the headquarters of the orthodox bishopric with the church of the Dormition (1649), the chapel (1841), the episcopal palace (secolul al XVII-lea), the old seminary (1838), the chancellery (19th century), gate belfry and the compound wall (18th century); the Vergu-M\u0103n\u0103il\u0103 mansion (18th century, which currently hosts the ethnography exhibit of the County Museum); Vasile Voiculescu County Library (1914); and the Communal Palace (city hall, 1899\u20131903).<ref name=\"patrimoniu.gov.ro_2015-07-132\" />\n\nOne public forum monument and twelve memorial monuments are included in the list of historical monuments in Buz\u0103u County with local importance, including the urban area of Cuza Vod\u0103 street (19th century) in the old town, [[Cr\u00e2ng park]], the Albatros Villa (that used to belong to [[Alexandru Marghiloman]]) and the park, the Jewish temple, the buildings of [[Colegiul Na\u021bional B.P. Hasdeu|B.P. Hasdeu]] and [[Mihai Eminescu National College (Buz\u0103u)|Mihai Eminescu]] high-schools, a house where [[Hortensia Papadat-Bengescu]] lived for a few years, and some of the tombs in Dumbrava cemetery, such as one that was originally decorated with the statue \"Prayer\" by [[Constantin Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i]] (nowadays replaced by a replica).<ref name=\"patrimoniu.gov.ro_2015-07-132\">{{Citation|title=List of historical monuments in Buz\u0103u|date=|url=http://patrimoniu.gov.ro/images/LMI/LMI-2010_BZ.pdf|author=|newspaper=Patrimoniu.gov.ro|accessdate=13 July 2015}}</ref>{{clearright}}\n\n==Geography==\nThe city is located in the center of the county, 100&nbsp;km north-east of [[Bucure\u0219ti|Bucharest]], in the South-East of Romania, taking up a total area of 81,3&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>, at the outermost curvature of the Subcarpathian foothills, at the crossroads of the three main Romanian historical provinces: [[Wallachia]], [[Transylvania]] and [[Moldavia]]. It is entirely placed on the right bank of [[Buz\u0103u (river)|Buz\u0103u river]], which forms its northern limit. The shape of the city is oblong, longer along the river and shorter across. It reaches altitudes of 101 meters in the North-West, near the foothills, going down to 88 meters on the river bank, while the average altitude of 95 meters is the same as the altitude of Dacia square, in the city center.<ref name=\"relief2\">Petcu, pp. 102\u2013103</ref> Thus, Buz\u0103u is placed in a flat area, with a height difference of just 10 meters along a 4 kilometer line.<ref name=\"relief2\" />\n\n{{wide image|RO BZ panorama of Buzau from DN2B.jpg|1200px|Panoramic view of the west side of Buz\u0103u seen from [[Coste\u0219ti, Buz\u0103u|Sp\u0103taru]], on national road [[DN2B]]. The Curvature Subcarpathians are noticeable at the left. Main landmarks seen, starting from the left: the Ursus brewery at the edge of Simileasca district, apartment buildings of Micro 14 district, [[Cr\u00e2ng park|Cr\u00e2ng park and forest]], Ice Magic skating rink, [[Stadionul Municipal, Buz\u0103u|the City Stadium]], Micro 12/Independen\u021bei district}}\n\n=== Waterways ===\n[[Buz\u0103u (river)|Buz\u0103u river]] is the northern limit of the city. This river has created an underground basin that it permanently fuels with water.<ref>Strategia Buz\u0103u 2014\u20132020, p. 15</ref> These underground waters are a main source of drinking water, and their excess overflows to a marshy wetland south of the city, in the neighboring communes [[Coste\u0219ti, Buz\u0103u|Coste\u0219ti]], [[St\u00e2lpu]] and [[\u021ainte\u0219ti]], with small but steady [[River source|springs]], that ultimately form the [[C\u0103lm\u0103\u021bui River (Br\u0103ila)|C\u0103lm\u0103\u021bui river]].<ref>Planul Urbanistic General, pagina 6</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nAnnual rainfall is circa 500&nbsp;mm<ref name=\"clima2\">Petcu, pp.104\u2013105</ref> and in winter the snow cover can be as high as 30&nbsp;cm.<ref name=\"clima2\" /> Buz\u0103u river has a fluctuating flow. Especially in spring, when it collects melted snow from the mountain area, its level rises. The city was, however, built away from its deep and wide valley, so the river never floods the city. Even at the major floods of 2005, the waters caused no problem in the city proper, but it seriously damaged both bridges across it located in the city,<ref name=\"jurnalul2005-05-10\">{{Citation|title=Podul de la Maracineni \u2013 Moldova, rupta de Muntenia|date=10 May 2005|url=http://jurnalul.ro/stiri/observator/podul-de-la-maracineni-moldova-rupta-de-muntenia-45374.html|author=Costisitor. Circulatia A Fost Deviata Pe Rute Ocolitoare|newspaper=Jurnalul Na\u021bional|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref> which is also protected by levees, and by the small C\u00e2nde\u0219ti dam, north-west of Buz\u0103u.<ref>Planul Urbanistic General, Raportul de Mediu, partea I, pp. 24&#x2013;25</ref> The local authorities consider, however, that their strategy of defense against flood does not adequately cover the city's belt road, part of [[DN2]], which follows the river for a short stretch.<ref>Strategia Buzau 2014\u20132020, pp 25&#x2013;26, 31</ref>\n\nThe climate is [[Humid continental climate|humid continental]], with an average 92&nbsp;freezing days a year (16 with temperatures below \u221210&nbsp;\u00b0C), but also with 92&nbsp;days of hot summer.<ref name=\"clima2\" /> Local winds include the [[Criv\u0103\u021b (v\u00e2nt)|Criv\u0103\u021b]], a cold north-easterly and sometimes easterly wind in winter, and the [[Austru]], a south-westerly wind that brings dry air in summer and leads to warmer days in winter.<ref>Jude\u021bele Rom\u00e2niei Socialiste, p. 161</ref>\n\nAverage, minimum and maximum temperatures, recorded until 2006, are present in the table below. In recent years, the average temperature of July went significantly higher than 22&nbsp;\u00b0C,<ref name=\"Meteoromania.ro_2017-10-19\">{{Citation|title=Average temperatures in July 2017 in Romania|date=|url=http://www.meteoromania.ro/images/anm_maps/temperature_07_2017.png|author=National Meteorological Administration of Romania|newspaper=Meteoromania.ro|accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref> which pushes Buz\u0103u from the [[Humid continental climate|Dfb/Dfa limit to inside the Dfa zone]] in the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] (see also [[Climate of Romania]]).<ref name=\"bio-conferences.org_2017-10-19\">{{Citation|title=Modifications in climate suitability for wine production of Romanian wine regions as a result of climate change|date=4 July 2017|url=https://www.bio-conferences.org/articles/bioconf/full_html/2017/02/bioconf-oiv2017_01026/bioconf-oiv2017_01026.html#R11|author=Liviu Mihai Irimia, Cristian Valeriu Patriche, Bogdan Ro\u015fca and Valeriu V. Cotea|accessdate=19 October 2017}}; data and further sources cited by this paper.</ref>\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"margin: 0 1em 0 1em; text-align:center\" width=\"90%\"\n! colspan=\"14\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#ccccff;\" |'''Average temperatures (monthly, per year)'''*\n|- style=\"background:#DCDCDC\"\n!Perioada\n!Jan\n!Feb\n!Mar\n!Apr\n!May\n!Jun\n!Jul\n!Aug\n!Sep\n!Oct\n!Nov\n!Dec\n!All year\n|-\n|1901\u20132000\n| \u22122,2\u00b0\n| \u22120,2\u00b0\n|4,4\u00b0\n|10,9\u00b0\n|15,9\u00b0\n|19,4\u00b0\n|21,4\u00b0\n|21,9\u00b0\n|17,4\u00b0\n|11,2\u00b0\n|5,1\u00b0\n|0,4\u00b0\n|10,7\u00b0\n|-\n|2005\n|1,7\u00b0\n| \u22121,3\u00b0\n|4,1\u00b0\n|10,6\u00b0\n|17,4\u00b0\n|19,0\u00b0\n|22,4\u00b0\n|22,0\u00b0\n|18,3\u00b0\n|11,9\u00b0\n|4,8\u00b0\n|1,6\u00b0\n|11,0\u00b0\n|-\n! colspan=\"14\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#ccccff;\" |'''Minimum and maximum temperatures per month during 1901\u20132000'''\n|- style=\"background:#DCDCDC\"\n|Year\n|1936\n|1990\n|1947\n|1909;1947\n|1950\n|1908\n|'''2000'''\n|1951\n|1946\n|1952\n|1963\n|1989\n|\n|-\n|'''Maximum'''\n|18,4\u00b0\n|22,2\u00b0\n|27,9\u00b0\n|31,5\u00b0\n|37,3\u00b0\n|38,5\u00b0\n|'''39,8\u00b0'''\n|39,7\u00b0\n|37,0\u00b0\n|35,3\u00b0\n|25,0\u00b0\n|21,6\u00b0\n|\n|- style=\"background:#DCDCDC\"\n|Year\n|'''1942'''\n|1929\n|1901\n|1944\n|1915\n|1973\n|1902\n|1939\n|1977\n|1988\n|1975\n|1902\n|\n|-\n|'''Minimum'''\n|'''-29,6\u00b0'''\n| \u221225,0\u00b0\n| \u221217,0\u00b0\n| \u22125,3\u00b0\n| \u22122,0\u00b0\n|4,6\u00b0\n|7,5\u00b0\n|5,4\u00b0\n| \u22122,0\u00b0\n| \u22128,0\u00b0\n| \u221217,6\u00b0\n| \u221223,0\u00b0\n|}\n<div style=\"text-align:center\"><small>''*Statistical Yearbook of Romania, 2006''</small></div>\n\n===Flora and fauna===\n[[File:RO_BZ_Buzau_Crang_east_island_1.jpg|right|thumb|Cr\u00e2ng park, the main green area]]\nThe flora of Buz\u0103u is more diverse in the western forest of Cr\u00e2ng, 189 ha of [[oak]] forest, a remainder of the ancient [[Codrii Vl\u0103siei]].  [[Cr\u00e2ng park|The Cr\u00e2ng park itself]] takes up 10 hectares of this forest and makes up the main green area of Buz\u0103u. It is not designated as a protected area itself, but a few species of plants are protected inside it, such as the ''[[fritillaria meleagris]]'' and ''[[iris brandzae]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.anpm.ro/anpm_resources/migrated_content/files/APM%20Buzau/Biodiversitate/Cadru%20general/3FlorajudetuluiBuzau.doc|title=Flora jude\u021bului Buz\u0103u|publisher=[[Agen\u021bia Na\u021bional\u0103 pentru Protec\u021bia Mediului|ANPM]]|accessdate=2015-04-28|trans-title=Flora of Buz\u0103u County|language=ro}}</ref> In the neighboring communes of [[\u021ainte\u0219ti]] and [[Coste\u0219ti, Buz\u0103u|Coste\u0219ti]] there are other remainders of Codrii Vl\u0103siei{{mdash}} Frasinu and Sp\u0103taru forests, respectively. In the yard of the building at the intersection of Crizantemelor and Tudor Vladimirescu streets, across the street from the park in front of B. P. Hasdeu high school and the Banu church, there is a century-old [[oak]], locally protected as a monument of nature.<ref>Strategia Buz\u0103u 2014\u20132020, p. 45</ref> 6% of the [[Lunca Buz\u0103ului]] protected area, a Natura 2000 site managed by the Ecological University of Bucharest, lies within city limits, in the north and east.<ref name=\"natura2000.mmediu.ro_2015-06-02\">{{Citation|title=Lunca Buz\u0103ului|date=|url=http://natura2000.mmediu.ro/site/93/rosci0103.html|author=|newspaper=Natura2000.mmediu.ro|accessdate=2 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150112210555/http://natura2000.mmediu.ro/site/93/rosci0103.html|archive-date=12 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMost of the streets in Buz\u0103u have trees planted alongside, [[chestnut]] on Nicolae B\u0103lcescu boulevard and [[Tilia|linden]] on Unirii boulevard. In their gardens, the locals grow [[rose]]s, [[Hyacinthus orientalis|hyacinths]], [[tulip]]s, local [[Paeonia peregrina|peonies]], and [[petunia]], as well as [[Vitis|grapevines]] and [[Parthenocissus quinquefolia|Virginia creepers]] for shade. The wild fauna in Buz\u0103u is made up of city-dwelling species. The [[house sparrow]] and the [[Eurasian collared dove|collared dove]] are ubiquitous, and the most present small mammals are the [[European polecat|wild polecat]] and the [[brown rat]]. Lakes are populated with small fish, such as [[European bitterling|bitterlings]] and [[eel]], as well as [[snail]]s and [[Balkan green lizard|green lizards]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Petcu|pp=106\u2013108}}</ref>\n\nDuring the migration season, a parliament of [[short-eared owl]]s has made a habit of spending a few days in some tall fir trees located in the yard of the Forestry Inspector's Office in the city center.<ref name=\"adev2015-04-30\">{{Citation|title=VIDEO Revenirea bufni\u021belor \u00een centrul Buz\u0103ului, semn al prim\u0103verii timpurii|date=24 February 2015|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/buzau/video-revenirea-bufnitelor-centrul-buzaului-semn-primaverii-timpurii-1_54ec6ffe448e03c0fdf0fcd2/index.html|author=Iulian Bunila|newspaper=Adev\u0103rul|accessdate=30 April 2015|trans-title=The arrival of owls in downtown Buz\u0103u, a sign of early spring|language=ro}}</ref> Experimental crops from the city's Research and Development Station for [[Olericulture]] sometimes attract [[Carpathian boar|wild boars]] from the riverside forests.<ref name=\"adev2017-06-20\">{{Citation|title=VIDEO Turm\u0103 de mistre\u0163i, la doar un kilometru distan\u0163\u0103 de centrul Buz\u0103ului|date=20 June 2017|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/buzau/video-turma-porci-mistreti-mai-putin-kilometru-centrul-buzaului-1_59492e5b5ab6550cb853d73c/index.html|author=Iulian Bunila|newspaper=Adev\u0103rul|accessdate=19 October 2017|trans-title=A sounder of boars, only a kilometer away from the center of Buz\u0103u|language=ro}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n<div style=\"float:left\">{{Pie chart|thumb=left|caption=Ethnic composition of Buz\u0103u|label1=Romanians|value1=88.42|color1=#8080ff|label2=Roma|value2=4.73|color2=#80ffff|label3=Unknown|value3=6.69|color3=#9f9f9f|label4=Others|value4=0.14|color4=#555555}}{{Pie chart|thumb=left|style=clear:none;|caption=Religious composition of Buz\u0103u|label1=Orthodox Christians|value1=91.98|color1=#8080ff|label2=Unknown|value2=6.74|color2=#c0c0c0|label3=Other religions|value3=1.27|color3=#9f9f9f}}</div>According to the 2011 census, the city has {{formatnum:115494}} inhabitants, a decrease from the previous census, in 2002, when {{formatnum:134227}}&nbsp;had been recorded.<ref name=\"kia.hu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kia.hu/konyvtar/erdely/erd2002/etnii2002.zip|title=Recens\u0103m\u00e2ntul Popula\u021biei \u0219i al Locuin\u021belor 2002 \u2013 popula\u021bia unit\u0103\u021bilor administrative pe etnii|publisher=Kultur\u00e1lis Innov\u00e1ci\u00f3s Alap\u00edtv\u00e1ny (KIA.hu \u2013 Funda\u021bia Cultural\u0103 pentru Inova\u021bie)|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Most inhabitants are [[Romanians]] (88.43%), with a [[Romani people in Romania|Roma]] minority (4.73%). Ethnic affiliation is unknown for 6.69% of the population.<ref name=\"insse_2011_nat\">Rezultatele finale ale Recens\u0103m\u00e2ntului din 2011: {{Cite web|url=http://www.recensamantromania.ro/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sR_Tab_8.xls|title=Tab8. Popula\u021bia stabil\u0103 dup\u0103 etnie \u2013 jude\u021be, municipii, ora\u0219e, comune|publisher=[[Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103]] din Rom\u00e2nia|accessdate=5 August 2013 |date=July 2013}}</ref> Most inhabitants practice [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christianity]] (91.98%). Religious affiliation is unknown for 6.75% of the population.<ref name=\"insse_2011_rel\">Rezultatele finale ale Recens\u0103m\u00e2ntului din 2011: {{Cite web|url=http://www.recensamantromania.ro/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sR_TAB_13.xls|title=Tab13. Popula\u021bia stabil\u0103 dup\u0103 religie \u2013 jude\u021be, municipii, ora\u0219e, comune|publisher=[[Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103]] din Rom\u00e2nia|accessdate=5 August 2013 |date=July 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Ethnic communities ===\nThe main ethnic minority in the city are the [[Romani people of Romania|Roma]]. Throughout history, other communities have existed in Buz\u0103u, but nowadays they are nearly extinct. Those that left their mark the most on the city were the [[History of the Jews in Romania|Jewish people]] and the [[Bulgarians in Romania|Bulgarians]].\n\n==== Roma ====\nSettled after the 16th century by the Orthodox bishopric on its estate located north-west of the market town of Buz\u0103u, in Simileasca and Iorguleasca villages, Roma people have lived as [[Slavery in Romania|slaves]] who worked on the bishopric's land.<ref name=\"Lahovari_Sim\">{{cite book|title=Simileasca (Iorguleasca), com. rur.|volume=5|page=389}}</ref> After they were freed in the 19th century and, with the union between Wallachia and Moldavia, the new country got a new territorial division, Simileasca became a commune. In 1968, this commune was dissolved and integrated with Buz\u0103u. The Roma community is still located mostly in this part of the city, and it preserves its identity, although its leaders believe that Roma people in other parts of the city, who no longer speak their people's language, accept assimilation by the majority Romanians, and declare themselves Romanian at the census.<ref name=\"stradadebuzau.ro_2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=\u021aiganii din Simileasca n-au nicio jen\u0103 s\u0103-\u0219i declare etnia \u2013 Strada de Buzau|date=|url=http://www.stradadebuzau.ro/tiganii-din-simileasca-n-au-nicio-jena-sa-si-declare-etnia/|author=Corina R\u0103chi\u021beanu|newspaper=Stradadebuzau.ro|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> The community is faced with endemic poverty, high illiteracy, lack of professional qualifications and high school dropout rates, which all expose it to permanently being manipulated by politicians for elections.<ref name=\"jurnalul2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=Tiganii din Simileasca asteapta Marea Chefuiala|date=24 May 2004|url=http://jurnalul.ro/special-jurnalul/tiganii-din-simileasca-asteapta-marea-chefuiala-68413.html|author=Tatiana Dabija|newspaper=Jurnalul Na\u021bional|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> Many Roma people went abroad, especially in the countries of Northern Europe.<ref name=\"adev2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=Norvegienii finan\u021beaz\u0103 proiecte de \u00eembun\u0103t\u0103\u021bire a vie\u021bii romilor din Buz\u0103u|date=7 February 2014|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/buzau/norvegienii-finanteaza-proiecte-imbunatatire-vietii-romilor-buzau-1_52f53da8c7b855ff5628bb51/index.html|author=Iulian Bunila|newspaper=Adev\u0103rul|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ziaristionline.ro_2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=\u021aiganii pe care nu-i vede Mircea Toma. \"Tiggarna\" \u2013 Cer\u0219etorii care au invadat Bor\u00e5s \u00een Suedia vin din Buz\u0103u, satul Similesca. Foto reportaj Bor\u00e5s Tidning \u0219i George Lixandru \u2013 Ziaristi Online|date=|url=http://www.ziaristionline.ro/2015/03/28/tiganii-pe-care-nu-i-vede-mircea-toma-tiggarna-cersetorii-care-au-invadat-boras-in-suedia-vin-din-buzau-satul-similesca-foto-reportaj-boras-tidning-si-george-lixandru/|author=George Lixandru|newspaper=Ziaristionline.ro|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> The municipality also runs programs to improve theirs status, and School no. 14, located in Simileasca, is the main focus of these actions.<ref name=\"ziaristionline.ro_2015-04-28\" /> Pupils of this school publish a bilingual school newspaper, in [[Romani language|Romani]] and [[Romanian language|Romanian]], which promotes Roma integration into society.<ref name=\"opiniabuzau.ro_2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=Fiica regelui Cioab\u0103, cooptat\u0103 \u00een editarea revistei bilingve pentru romii din Simileasca|date=|url=http://opiniabuzau.ro/fiica-regelui-cioaba-cooptata-in-editarea-revistei-bilingve-pentru-romii-din-simileasca|author=Silvia Herghelegiu|newspaper=Opinia|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Jews ====\n[[File:RO_BZ_Jewish_temple_2.jpg|right|thumb|The Jewish synagogue in Buz\u0103u]]\nAlthough mentioned in documents as early as the 16th century, the [[Jews]] of Buz\u0103u became an especially important community starting with the cultural and economical development period of the 19th century. A large proportion of them were merchants and craftsmen. The Jewish cemetery appeared in 1853 and a temple dates from 1885. Between the two World Wars, 10% of the population of Buz\u0103u was Jewish,<ref name=\"adev2013-04-11\">{{Citation|title=VIDEO Cimitirul evreiesc din Buz\u0103u, un ansamblu monumental ruinat de trecera timpului \u0219i nep\u0103sarea oamenilor|date=11 April 2013|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/buzau/buzau-cimitir-evrei-1_5166524600f5182b85a74909/index.html|author=Iulian Bunila|newspaper=Adev\u0103rul|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> a large percentage compared to other cities in Wallachia, but significantly smaller than those in Moldavia, which saved the community from the brunt of the [[Ion Antonescu#Antonescu and the Holocaust|repression by Antonescu's government]]. Still, during [[World War II]], the Jews had to endure some persecutions: obligated to do compulsory work (authorities abused of the law, and extended the age of the people who had to do this work, as well as the body of the work itself), and to pay 15 million lei (four times the tax) for \"The Reunification Loan\"; certain types of objects were confiscated from them and special restrictions were imposed. The community had to host orphans whose parents had died in [[Holocaust|the Holocaust]], before they were deported to [[Transnistria Governorate|Transnistria]].<ref name=\"doctorat_maracineanu\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.unibuc.ro/studies/Doctorate2013Mai/MARACINEANU%20LAURA%20-%20COMUNITATEA%20EVREIASCA%20DE%20LA%20BUZAU%20IN%20TIMPUL%20CELUI%20DE%20AL%20DOILEA%20RAZBOI%20MONDIAL/rezumat%20maracineanu.doc|title=Comunitatea evreiasc\u0103 de la Buz\u0103u \u00een timpul celui de al Doilea R\u0103zboi Mondial|first1=Mirela-Laura|last1=M\u0103r\u0103cineanu|first2=Ion (coordonator)|last2=Bulei|publisher=Facultatea de Istorie, [[Universitatea din Bucure\u0219ti]]|year=2012}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (rezumat)</ref> During these persecutions, the Jewish community was defended by captains Stroie and Ionescu, by the Sc\u00e2nteie and Stahu families,<ref name=\"romanianjewish.org_2015-04-28\" /> and by [[Anghel Anu\u021boiu]] from Vrancea, a man who informed members of the community of upcoming Nazi raids, saving many lives, including that of Rabbi Simon Bercovich, whom he aided to leave the city and go into hiding.<ref name=\"evz2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=Lista lui b\u0103di\u021ba Anghel, salvatorul de evrei|date=11 January 2008|url=http://www.evz.ro/lista-lui-badita-anghel-salvatorul-de-evrei-2886.html|author=|newspaper=Evenimentul zilei|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://db.yadvashem.org/righteous/family.html?language=en&itemId=4044236|title=Anu\u021boiu, Anghel T.|publisher=Yad Vashem, baza de date a drep\u021bilor \u00eentre popoare|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref> After the war, most Jews of the city moved to [[Israel]], and left behind a Jewish community of only a few tens of people. Some of the personalities of the Jewish community in Buz\u0103u were painter [[Margareta Sterian]] and philosopher [[Ludwig Grunberg]].<ref name=\"romanianjewish.org_2015-04-28\">{{Citation|title=Obstea evreiasca buzoiana|date=|url=http://romanianjewish.org/ro/?page_id=737#i8|author=|newspaper=Romanianjewish.org|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Bulgarians (\"Serbs\") ====\nIn the 18th century, to avoid [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] repression against Christians in the Balkans, groups of Bulgarians settled in [[\u021aara Rom\u00e2neasc\u0103|Wallachia]] where they enjoyed freedom to practice Christianity; some of these groups came to Buz\u0103u. The locals called them \"Serbs\" as a generic term for South-Slavs. The new immigrants soon started developing [[Olericulture|vegetable gardens]] as their houses were in the vicinity of the river that provided them with plenty of water, while local farmers were focusing more on raising livestock and growing cereals. Although the Bulgarian community was in time assimilated by the Romanians, to this day locals use the word \"Serb\" as a synonym to \"one who grows vegetables\".<ref name=\"bulgari\">{{Harvnb|Petcu|2002|pp=27\u201334}}</ref>\n\n== Government ==\nBuz\u0103u is administered by a mayor and a local council made up of 23 councillors. The mayor, Constantin Toma, of the [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party (PSD)]], has been in office since 2016.<ref name=\"hotnews.ro_2016-10-27\">{{Citation | url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-politic-21056696-rezultate-alegeri-locale-2016-buzau-constantin-toma-psd.htm| title=Industriasul Constantin Toma (PSD) a castigat primaria Buzau \u2013 Politic| newspaper=HotNews.ro| date= 6 June 2016| author=Red. Stiri| accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> Beginning with the 2016 local elections, the local council has the following political makeup:<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/Export_mandate-2.xlsx|format=XLSX|title=Lista competitorilor care au ob\u021binut mandate|trans-title=List of candidates that obtained mandates|publisher=Biroul Electoral Central pentru alegerile locale din 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Party\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Seats\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" colspan=\"12\" | Current Council\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party (PSD)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''11'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party (PNL)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''5'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| [[People's Movement Party|People's Movement Party (PMP)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (Romania)|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (ALDE)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}}| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#ac211a\" | &nbsp;\n| [[Romanian Social Party|Romanian Social Party (PSRo)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| bgcolor=\"#ac211a\" | &nbsp;\n| bgcolor=\"#ac211a\" | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#aaa\" | &nbsp;\n| Independent\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''1'''\n| bgcolor=\"#aaa\" | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|}\nBuz\u0103u is not subdivided into any lower units, but local authorities guide their projects and strategies according to an informal division by districts. In ''Strategia 2014\u20132020'', a strategical document of the mayor's office, the following districts of Buz\u0103u were identified: Center, Micro 12/Indepeneden\u021bei, Marghiloman, Doroban\u021bi, Nicolae B\u0103lcescu, Simileasca, Micro 14, Po\u0219t\u0103, Mihai Viteazul, Pod Horticolei, Luceaf\u0103rul, Bro\u0219teni and the Industrial Zone.<ref>Strategia Buz\u0103u 2014\u20132020, pp. 87\u201398</ref>\n\nBuz\u0103u takes on the administrative role of capital of [[Buz\u0103u County]], therefore almost all county-level public services are headquartered there. Additionally, at national level, Buz\u0103u is the headquarters of the [[2nd Infantry Division (Romania)|2nd Infantry Division]] (''Getica''; former 2nd Romanian Army), one of the three divisions that make up the [[Romanian Land Forces]],<ref name=\"adev2015-01-27\">{{Citation | url=http://adevarul.ro/international/europa/maresalul-primit-onorul-divizia-2-infanterie-getica-1_524d38aac7b855ff56f41a74/index.html| title=Mare\u0219alul care a primit onorul la Divizia 2 Infanterie \"Getica\"| newspaper=Adev\u0103rul| date= 3 October 2013| author=Ion Petrescu| accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> as well as three battalions under its command{{mdash}} one of engineers, one of signals,<ref name=\"arhiva.gov.ro_2015-01-27\">{{Citation | url=http://arhiva.gov.ro/aniversarea-batalionului-47-comunicatii-si-informatica__l1a63269.html| title=Aniversarea Batalionului 47 Comunica\u021bii \u0219i Informatic\u0103| newspaper=Arhiva.gov.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> and one of logistics. Near the city, in the village of [[Cochirleanca|Boboc]], there is a military aviation school.\n\nThe highest court functioning in the city is the Buz\u0103u Tribunal, with authority over the entire county.<ref name=\"csm1909.ro_2015-04-21\">{{Citation | url=http://old.csm1909.ro/csm/index.php?cmd=9401| title=Prezentarea sistemului judiciar rom\u00e2n|trans-title=Presentation of the Romanian justice system|language=ro| publisher=Superior Magistrates' Council| date= | author=| accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> The jurisdiction of the Tribunal covers all the four local courts (''judec\u0103torii'') in the County, of which Buz\u0103u Local Court is in the city and takes cases related to Buz\u0103u and 34 surrounding communes, the largest jurisdiction of the four.<ref name=\"legex.ro_2015-04-21\">{{Citation | url=http://www.legex.ro/Hotararea-337-1993-4117.aspx| title=Hot\u0103r\u00e2rea 337/1993|trans-title=Resolution no. 337/1993| newspaper=Legex.ro| date= | author=Romanian Government| accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> The higher court to all these is the Court of Appeals in Ploie\u0219ti.<ref name=\"just.ro_2015-04-21\">{{Citation| url=http://www.just.ro/Sectiuni/SistemulJudiciar%C3%AEnRom%C3%A2nia/Legeaprivindorganizareajudiciar%C4%83nr3042004/tabid/275/Default.aspx| title=Legea privind organizarea judiciar\u0103 nr. 304/2004| trans-title=Judicial Organization Law no. 304/2004| publisher=Romanian Ministry of Justice| date=| author=Romanian Parliament| accessdate=21 April 2015}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn the Romanian Parliament, Buz\u0103u elects deputies on the lists associated with [[Buz\u0103u County]]. Of the seven deputies elected in 2016 on these lists, six ([[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|social-democrats]] [[Marcel Ciolacu]], [[Ionela Viorela Dobric\u0103]], [[Sorin Laz\u0103r]], [[D\u0103nu\u021b P\u0103le]], [[Nicolaie-Sebastian-Valentin Radu]]; and [[Adrian Mocanu]] from the [[People's Movement Party]]) have their office in Buz\u0103u, while only the [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|liberal]] [[Cristinel Romanescu]] has his in [[R\u00e2mnicu S\u0103rat]].<ref name=\"Camera Deputa\u021bilor_2017-04-24\">{{Citation | url=http://www.cdep.ro/pls/parlam/structura2015.de?leg=2016&par=C| title=Lista deputatilor \u2013 informatii de contact| newspaper=Camera Deputa\u021bilor| date= | author=Romanian Chamber of Deputies| accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 19th century, local statesman [[Alexandru Marghiloman]], owner of a large estate and a mansion near the city, became prominent.<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://www.opiniabuzau.ro/index.php/istorii-buzoiene/2323-radiografii-subiective-alexandru-marghiloman-lordul-valah-i|title=Radiografii subiective \u2013 Alexandru Marghiloman \u2013 lordul valah (I)|publisher=Opinia|location=Buz\u0103u|date=27 June 2011|accessdate=2013-12-06|first=Nicolae|last=Pene\u0219}}</ref> Germanofile, Marghiloman was prime minister around the end of [[World War I]], when Romania was compelled to sign the [[Treaty of Bucharest (1918)|Treaty of Bucharest]] of 1918 and began the process of integrating [[Bessarabia]], which had proclaimed its union with Romania in mid-April of that year.<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://www.historia.ro/exclusiv_web/general/articol/unirea-basarabiei-romania-documente|title=Unirea Basarabiei cu Rom\u00e2nia \u00een documente|publisher=Historia.ro|accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref> Another known contemporary politician from Buz\u0103u is [[C\u0103t\u0103lin Predoiu]]; initially, an independent Minister of Justice in the government of [[C\u0103lin Popescu-T\u0103riceanu]],<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-politic-2476877-catalin-marian-predoiu-noul-ministru-justitiei.htm|title=Catalin Marian Predoiu, noul ministru al Justitiei|author=Dumitrina Galantonu|date=29 February 2008|accessdate=2013-12-06|publisher=[[Hotnews.ro]]}}</ref> Predoiu became a member of the National Liberal Party (PNL), after which he quit in 2008 to continue as minister, and in 2013 has attempted to obtain the presidential nomination of the [[Democratic Liberal Party (Romania)|Democratic Liberal Party]] for the next year's election;<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/evenimentul-zilei-tv-invitatul-de-astazi-este-catalin-preda-1068668.html|title=Evenimentul zilei TV. C\u0103t\u0103lin Predoiu s-ar retrage din lupta pentru preziden\u021biale dac\u0103 un alt candidat de dreapta ar avea \u0219anse mai mari|publisher=[[Evenimentul Zilei]]|first=Alexandra|last=Ciliac|accessdate=2013-12-06|date=21 November 2013}}</ref> eventually, that party merged with the PNL, who nominated Klaus Iohannis, and Predoiu became shadow prime-minister.<ref name=\"evz2015-04-21\">{{Citation | url=http://www.evz.ro/vasile-blaga-catalin-predoiu-prim-ministru-desemnat-al-aliantei-noastre.html| title=Vasile Blaga: C\u0103t\u0103lin Predoiu, prim-ministru desemnat al alian\u021bei noastre| newspaper=Evenimentul zilei| date= 11 August 2014| author=Andreea Udrea| accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n\n=== Economic history ===\nDuring the Middle Ages, Buz\u0103u's economy was based on trade, as the market town began as a customs and exchange point, and developed due to its position at the curvature of the Carpathians, in a plase where roads that connected Wallachia to [[Moldova|Moldavia]] and [[Transilvania|Transylvania]] met. The old market town tradition is still preserved in the ''Dr\u0103gaica'' fair, held every June around [[Midsummer]], bringing together small producers and merchants from diverse regions of Romania.\n\nThe agricultural reform during [[Alexandru Ioan Cuza]] led some of the Bulgarian gardners to rent in 1897 \u0219i 1898 some land acquired by the state from the bishopric. The developed a distribution network for their produce both in Buz\u0103u, and in other nearby cities such as [[Bra\u0219ov]], [[Ploie\u0219ti]] or [[R\u00e2mnicu S\u0103rat]]. Their activity became even more lucrative after the land reform of 1921.<ref>Petcu, 2002, p. 134</ref>\n\nAfter the period of repeated invasions and destruction ended in the 19th century, the economy began to industrialize as well. Towards the end of that century, the development of a Romanian railway network made Buz\u0103u one of its important hubs and pushed the small craftsmen's shops to evolve into industrial installations. The first such facility was the ''Garoflid mill'', open in 1883, that worked also as a [[Textile|cloth]] factory.<ref name=\"petcu1353\">Petcu, 2002, p. 135</ref> \u00cen 1894, an [[Petrol|oil]] refinery of the ''Saturn'' society was built; this refinery was to function for 50 years.\n\nAfter a dramatic nationwide decrease caused by the [[First World War]] (the 1919 output was a quarter of the one in 1913<ref name=\"petcu1353\" />), the industrial development picked up steam during the interbellum. One of the main components of the local industry was [[Mill (grinding)|milling]]. The first industrial mill in the city, ''Garoflid'', renamed ''Zangopol'' after its new owner, had reached a capital of 5 million [[Romanian leu|lei]] in 1928 and, 30 de million in 1938, while the company that operated it had around 100 employees.<ref name=\"petcu1363\">Petcu, 2002, p. 136</ref> Another business started at this time was ''Metalurgica \u0219i Turn\u0103torie \u2013 S.A.'' (Metallurgy and Foundry), founded in 1928 with a capital of over 9 million lei. Although it had an initially difficult period, as it was closed during the [[Great Depression]], it was reopened in 1933, only to be closed again in 1940 and 1944, during World War II.<ref name=\"Buz\u0103u p. 255\" />\n[[File:1970_Intreprinderea_de_geamuri_Buzau.JPG|left|thumb|Buz\u0103u window factory in 1970]]\nAfter [[World War II]], on 11 June 1948 all factories were requisitioned by the Communist government, who also began a program of forced industrialization, even though some of the industries that were being developed were unfit to the region.<ref name=\"petcu1373\">Petcu, 2002, p. 137</ref> In 1965, the 318 [[Hectare|ha]] Buz\u0103u South industrial platform began to be built around the old location of the ''Saturn'' refinery, blown up during the war. It was the location of the city's most important factories that were developed at the time: the Steel Wire and Steel Wire Products Enterprise (after 1990, ''Ductil''), the Railway Machinery Enterprise (after 1990, ''[[VAE Apcarom|Apcarom]]''), ''Metalurgica'' (the one founded in 1928), the Glass and Windows Factory (after 1991, ''[[Gerom Buz\u0103u|Gerom S.A.]]'').\n[[File:RO_BZ_Contactoare.jpg|right|thumb|The \"Contactoare\" electrical relays factory in Buz\u0103u]]\nOther facilities were located in other parts of the city, such as the Contactors Enterprise, in the North-East, and the Plastic Works (after 1990, ''[[Romcarbon|Romcarbon S.A.]]'') in the North.\n\nDespite the forced industrialization, Buz\u0103u was spared from becoming dependent on a single industry, and there was no single point of failure for the city's economy. According to the new law of commerce of 1990, that came after the [[Romanian Revolution of 1989|fall of Communism]], these factories were organised as state-owned companies, and were privatised. Most of them survived the transition to a [[market economy]], as many of them thus became viable.\n\n=== Present economy ===\nCurrently, the largest Buz\u0103u-based company is Romet, a [[holding company]] made up of multiple firms that produse isolation materials for water and gas pipes, water filters, fire extinguishers and other related products. It was successful in the 1990s, with the ''Aquator'' home water purifier. In 1999, it also acquired ''Aromet S.A.'', the company that operated the 1928 ''Metalurgica'' factory.<ref>Petcu, p. 141</ref>\n[[File:Buzau_ductil.jpg|left|thumb|240x240px|Ductil steel wire factory]]\nOther Buz\u0103u-based companies were privatised by programs supervised by the [[World Bank]]. [[VAE Apcarom|''Apcarom S.A.'']], the only Romanian producer of railway equipments,<ref name=\"petcu1382\">Petcu, 2002, p. 138</ref> was acquired by the Austrian company VAE, and in 2008 had a capital of 7.38&nbsp;million lei.<ref name=\"curierulnational.ro_2006-07-31\">{{Citation|title=Profit in scadere pentru Apcarom|date=31 July 2006|url=http://www.curierulnational.ro/Economie/2006-07-31/Profit+in+scadere+pentru+Apcarom|author=|newspaper=Curierul Na\u021bional|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref> ''Ductil S.A.'', one of the largest companies in the city, was privatised in 1999 and divided subsequently, during 1999\u20132000 by the new majority shareholder, FRO Spa, who only kept the electrodes and welding equipment facilities, and sold out the others. The steel wire, welded metal net, concrete and iron works became [[Ductil Steel S.A.]] and passed to the Italian company Sidersipe.<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://old.standard.money.ro/articol_6897/constructiile_sporesc_afacerile_ductil_steel.html|title=Constructiile sporesc afacerile Ductil Steel|date=18 July 2007|accessdate=2008-02-22|publisher=Business Standard|archiveurl=http://www.construction-briefly.ro/articol/constructiile-sporesc-afacerile-ductil-steel|archivedate=18 July 2007}}</ref> The iron powder works became ''Ductil Iron Powder''. In 2007, FRO Spa sold ''Ductil S.A.'' to the Russian company [[Mechel]], for 90 million euro.<ref name=\"hotnews.ro_2007-10-5\">{{Citation|title=Rusii de la Mechel cumpara cu 90 mil. euro Ductil Buzau|date=5 October 2007|url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-arhiva-1020251-rusii-mechel-cumpara-90-mil-euro-ductil-buzau.htm|author=|newspaper=HotNews.ro|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref> ''Zah\u0103rul S.A.'', the town's sugar producer, was acquired by ''Agrana Rom\u00e2nia'', an Austrian-based group that also owned other sugar factories in [[Roman, Neam\u021b|Roman]], a starch factory in [[\u021a\u0103nd\u0103rei]] and a juice facility in [[Vaslui]].<ref name=\"zf.ro_2010-09-21\">{{Citation|title=Austriecii \u00eenchid fabrica de zah\u0103r de la Buz\u0103u timp de 4 luni|date=21 September 2010|url=http://www.zf.ro/companii/austriecii-inchid-fabrica-de-zahar-de-la-buzau-timp-de-4-luni-7357694|author=Diana Tudor Stoica|newspaper=Ziarul financiar|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nMilling is still present on the local market: the largest local producer is [[Boromir Prod]], controlled by businessman Constantin Boromiz,<ref name=\"zf.ro_2009-05-11\">{{Citation|title=Cum a ajuns Constantin Boromiz de la o moara in satul natal la un business de 150 de milioane de euro in panificatie|date=11 May 2009|url=http://www.zf.ro/companii/cum-a-ajuns-constantin-boromiz-de-la-o-moara-in-satul-natal-la-un-business-de-150-de-milioane-de-euro-in-panificatie-4333603/|author=Diana Tudor Stoica|newspaper=Ziarul financiar|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref> owner of the ''Boromir'' group, who also owns Boromir Ind V\u00e2lcea, Panmed [[Media\u0219]] and Comcereal [[Sibiu]].<ref name=\"zf.ro_2009-05-11\" /><ref>[http://www.wall-street.ro/tag/boromir-prod-buzau.html Scurt\u0103 prezentare \u0219i list\u0103 de \u0219tiri] asociate firmei Boromir Prod Buz\u0103u, pe website-ul [[Wall-street.ro]]. Accesat la 18 August 2015</ref>\n\nThe economy is still more oriented towards industry rather than services, which, according to a 2016 survey of the World Bank, made it more attractive to the labor force of lower qualification (at best with a high school degree). The same survey showed that most of the labor force in the city came from within the county, as Buz\u0103u is the center of a highly rural, compact and densely-populated area. The city was found to be in competition with larger cities for the labor force from other counties, a feature it shares with [[Alexandria, Romania|Alexandria]]. The proximity of Bucharest makes Buz\u0103u itself a source of internal migration, thus orbiting the capital city. Buz\u0103u is the second city (closely after [[Ploie\u0219ti]], a city with almost double the population), by the number of employees in Bucharest coming from other cities between 1991 and 2011; the survey points out that this has been a disadvantage, but might become an opportunity in the future.<ref>{{Citat web|url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/448771499322731333/pdf/116400-ROMANIAN-REVISED-PUBLIC-Magnet-Cities-Migration-and-Commuting-in-Romania-RO.pdf|title=Ora\u0219e-magnet. Migra\u021bie \u0219i navetism \u00een Rom\u00e2nia|author=Marius Cristea, Codru\u021ba Mare, Ciprian Moldovan, Andreea China, Thomas Farole, Adina Vin\u021ban, Jane Park, Keith Patrick Garrett \u0219i Marcel Ionescu-Heroiu|publisher=[[Banca Mondial\u0103]]|accessdate=27 July 2017}}, paginile 25, 40, 65</ref>\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:RO BZ Railway station.jpg|thumb|The main railway station in Buz\u0103u]]\n[[File:Buzau BMC bus 3.jpg|thumb|City bus on route 1, near the Buz\u0103u railway station]]\n\n===Rail===\nBuz\u0103u is one of the country's main important railway hubs, as it connects [[Bucharest]] and [[Ploie\u0219ti]] with [[Foc\u0219ani]], [[Gala\u021bi]] and [[Constan\u021ba]]. The city railway station was open in 1872, along with the Bucharest-Gala\u021bi railway.<ref name=\"hotnews.ro_2014-03-14\">{{Citation | url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-esential-16807977-analiza-cum-mergeau-trenurile-acum-140-ani-poveste-romani-unguri-austrieci-englezi-vremuri-scandaluri-rasunatoare-reusite-uimitoare.htm| title=ANALIZA Cum mergeau trenurile acum 140 de ani - O poveste cu romani, unguri, austrieci si englezi in vremuri cu scandaluri rasunatoare si reusite uimitoare - Esential| newspaper=HotNews.ro| date= 2014-03-13| author=Vlad Barza| accessdate=2015-06-02}}</ref>\n\nA branch of this railway, from Buz\u0103u to M\u0103r\u0103\u0219e\u0219ti was opened a few years later, on [[13 June]] [[1881]],<ref name=\"gds.ro_2011-02-05\">{{Citation | url=http://www.gds.ro/Local/2011-02-05/Calea+ferata+din+Romania++si+inceputurile+ei/| title=Calea ferat\u0103 din Rom\u00e2nia \u0219i \u00eenceputurile ei| newspaper=Gazeta de Sud| date= 5 February 2011 | author=| accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref> and it was the first railway designed by Romanian engineers.<ref name=\"agir.ro_2015-06-02\">{{Citation | url=http://www.agir.ro/istoric.php| title=Istoric|publisher=Asociatia Generala a Inginerilor din Romania| newspaper=Agir.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=2015-06-02}}</ref>\n\nThe Buz\u0103u-Nehoia\u0219u line, open in 1908, connects Buz\u0103u to the smaller towns and villages along the [[Buz\u0103u River]] valley, including [[Nehoiu]] and [[P\u0103t\u00e2rlagele]].<ref name=\"Nicolescu_Opinia\">{{Cite news|title=Linia C.F.R. Buzau - Nehoiasu, 100 de ani de la inaugurare (august 1909)|date=30 June 2009|first=Valeriu|last=Nicolescu|first2=Monica|last2=B\u0103nic\u0103|newspaper=Opinia|location=Buz\u0103u}}, a copy of that article is available online on the [http://www.transira.ro/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=3760 Transira forum]</ref>\n\n===Road===\nBuz\u0103u is crossed by national road [[DN2]] (part of [[European Road E85]]), which connects the city to [[Bucharest]] to the South and to [[R\u00e2mnicu S\u0103rat]] and the main cities of [[Western Moldavia]] to the North. National road [[DN1B]] (European Road E577) branches out of DN2 in Buz\u0103u. This road connects the city to [[Ploie\u0219ti]]. In the North of the city, [[DN10]] also branches from DN2. It crosses the Carpathians at their South-Eastern curvature through [[Buz\u0103u Pass]] towards [[Bra\u0219ov]]. The South of Buz\u0103u is also crossed by national road DN2B, which branches from DN2 \u00een the neighboring commune of Coste\u0219ti, leading eastward to Gala\u021bi and [[Br\u0103ila]]. In Buz\u0103u, county road DJ203D branches from DN2B. It leads South to [[\u021ainte\u0219ti, Buz\u0103u|\u021ainte\u0219ti]] and [[Smeeni, Buz\u0103u|Smeeni]], where it ends in [[DN2C]], a road along which it helps connect Buz\u0103u to [[Slobozia]].<ref>{{Google maps|accessdate=2015-04-28|url=https://www.google.ro/maps/@45.1446317,26.8161519,13z}}</ref>\n\nIn the Buz\u0103u city area, the only functional road bridge over Buz\u0103u River is the one crossing with DN2 to [[M\u0103r\u0103cineni, Buz\u0103u|M\u0103r\u0103cineni]]. There is another road bridge, connecting the city to [[Vadu Pa\u0219ii, Buz\u0103u|Vadu Pa\u0219ii]], near the railway bridge. It was however closed after it was destroyed by a flash flood in 2005, and repairs kept being postponed, which had an impact on the economy of the neighboring communes, North-East of the city, as it remains used only by pedestrians and cyclists.<ref name=\"adev2015-06-02\">{{Citation | url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/buzau/maternitatea-noua-podul-vadu-pasii-principalii-agenti-electorali-buzaului-1_5475895ba0eb96501e186dde/index.html| title=Maternitatea nou\u0103 \u0219i Podul Vadu Pa\u0219ii, principalii agen\u021bi electorali ai Buz\u0103ului| newspaper=Adev\u0103rul| date= 26 November 2014| author=Iulian Bunila| accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"stiri.tvr.ro_2015-06-02\">{{Citation | url=http://stiri.tvr.ro/podul-de-la-vadu-pasii-proiectat-de-anghel-saligny-e-inchis-traficului-auto_52467.html| title=Podul de la Vadu Pa\u0219ii, proiectat de Anghel Saligny, e \u00eenchis traficului auto| newspaper=Stiri.tvr.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> Works began in the fall of 2017.<ref name=\"adev2017-09-04\">{{Citation | url=https://adevarul.ro/locale/buzau/au-inceput-lucrarile-podul-vadu-pasii-marti-interzis-accesul-pietonilor-1_59ad7a7a5ab6550cb8a0ee48/index.html| title=VIDEO Au \u00eenceput lucr\u0103rile la podul de la Vadu Pa\u015fii. De mar\u0163i, va fi interzis accesul pietonilor| newspaper=Adev\u0103rul| date= 4 September 2017| author=Iulian Bunila| accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nTwo main bust stations, one in the North and one in the South next to the railway station, as well a few other secondary bus stops, are used by private transportation companies that operate services to other cities or nearby villages.<ref name=\"autogari.ro_2015-04-28\">{{Citation | url=http://www.autogari.ro/Buzau/| title=Autogari din Buzau, Romania si curse autocare, microbuze| newspaper=Autogari.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Air===\n\nBuz\u0103u has no civil airport. The only air transport infrastructure present in the city is the military airport and heliport South-West of the city, but it is used only by emergency sanitary flights.<ref>Strategia Buz\u0103u 2014-2020, pp 53&ndash;54</ref> Civil air traffic for Buz\u0103u is performed through [[Henri Coand\u0103 International Airport]] in [[Otopeni]], 110&nbsp;km away, the main air hub for Wallachia.<ref name=\"agerpres.ro_2015-06-02\">{{Citation | url=http://www.agerpres.ro/politica/2010/12/09/boagiu-vrem-sa-transformam-aeroportul-otopeni-in-aeroport-regional-iar-baneasa-in-aeroport-business-13-05-04| title=Boagiu: Vrem s\u0103 transform\u0103m Aeroportul Otopeni \u00een aeroport regional, iar B\u0103neasa \u00een aeroport business \u2013 AGERPRES| newspaper=Agerpres.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Public transportation===\n10 bus lines connect residential areas to industrial areas (including Buz\u0103u South industrial platform), the city center and the railway station.<ref name=\"transbusbuzau.ro_2015-04-28\">{{Citation | url=http://www.transbusbuzau.ro/index.php?subj=19| title=Harti Trasee - TransBus Buzau| newspaper=Transbusbuzau.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> There are a few taxi companies licensed by the city also operating in the surrounding villages.<ref name=\"reporterbuzoian.ro_2015-08-18\">{{Citation | url=http://reporterbuzoian.ro/cate-taxiuri-tranziteaza-zilnic-municipiul-buzau/| title=C\u00e2te taxiuri tranziteaz\u0103 zilnic municipiul Buz\u0103u?| newspaper=Reporterbuzoian.ro| date= | author=| accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Education and culture==\n[[File:RO BZ County library.jpg|thumb|The ''Vasile Voiculescu'' memorial county library in Buz\u0103u]]\n\nThe first school in Buz\u0103u was the school for church and icon painters, opened by Chesarie, the bishop of Buz\u0103u. The school functioned at the bishopric of Buz\u0103u, and was managed by [[Nicolae Teodorescu]]. [[Gheorghe Tattarescu]] started learning painting here.\n\nThe city's most important educational landmark is the [[Bogdan Petriceicu Hasdeu National College|''Bogdan Petriceicu Hasdeu'' National College]], attended by the Nobel prize winner [[George Emil Palade]] in his youth. The ''Hasdeu'' high school was inaugurated in 1867.\n\nThe city's public library was opened in 1893, under the name of ''[[Carol I]] Public Library''. Later it took the name of [[Vasile Voiculescu]], Buz\u0103u's most prominent author, writer, and poet.\n\n[[File:Colti amber museum.jpg|thumb|right|260px|Buz\u0103u County Museum]]\n\nThe ''George Ciprian'' stage theatre was created in 1996. It does not have an acting crew of its own, relying on contracts. Its first manager was playwright [[Paul Ioachim]].\n\nThe first university in the city was the Economic University College, inaugurated in 1992, a branch of the [[Academy of Economic Studies]] in [[Bucharest]].\n\nThe main museum in Buz\u0103u is the ''Buz\u0103u County Museum'', which exhibits items related to the region's history. The same museum oversees the [[ethnography]] exhibition at the [[Vergu-M\u0103n\u0103il\u0103 House]], as well as the ''[[Amber]] Museum'' in [[Col\u021bi]] and the ''Vasile Voiculescu Memorial House'' in [[P\u00e2rscov]].\n\n==Buz\u0103u natives==\n* [[Ion B\u0103ie\u0219u]], playwright\n* [[Constantin Budeanu]], electrical engineer\n* [[Vasile C\u00e2rlova]], poet\n* [[George Ciprian]], actor, playwright\n* [[Constantin C. Giurescu]], historian\n* [[\u0218tefan Gu\u0219\u0103]], Romanian Army general\n* [[Paul Ioachim]], actor, playwright\n* [[Mico Kaufman]], sculptor\n* [[Alexandru Marghiloman]], statesman, [[Prime Minister of Romania]]\n* [[Mihaela Runceanu]], pop singer\n* [[Radu G. Vl\u0103descu]], professor at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine at the [[University of Agronomical Sciences and Veterinary Medicine]], [[Bucharest]], member of the [[Romanian Academy]] and correspondent member of the [[French Academy]]\n* [[Vasile Voiculescu]], poet, writer, playwright\n\n===Prominent mayors===\n* [[Nicu Constantinescu]]\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Stan S\u0103raru|ro}}\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Romania}}\nBuz\u0103u is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n* [[Oudenaarde]], [[Belgium]], since 1999\n* [[Agios Dimitrios]], [[Greece]], since 2006\n* [[Soroca]], [[Moldova]], since 2012\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Buz\u0103u}}\n* {{cite book | first=Gheorghe | last=Petcu|author2=Constantin Stan |author3=Doina Ciobanu |author4=Constan\u021ba T\u0103nase |author5=Doina Filoti  | title = Municipiul Buz\u0103u. Monografie | location = Buz\u0103u | publisher = Editura Alpha| year = 2002|language=Romanian | isbn = 978-973-8054-81-3}}\n* {{cite book | first=Corneliu | last=\u0218tefan | title = La noapte, Cotidianul | location = Bucharest | publisher = Editura Eminescu| year = 1985|language=Romanian}}\n\n{{Buz\u0103u County}}\n{{Cities in Romania}}\n{{RoJudCapitals}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buzau}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Buz\u0103u County]]\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Capitals of Romanian counties]]\n[[Category:Localities in Muntenia]]\n[[Category:Buz\u0103u| ]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buz%C4%83u"}
{"title_page": "Muxuyuan station", "text_new": "{{short description|Nanjing Metro station}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name             = Muxuyuan\n| native_name      = \u660e\u5b5d\u9675\u2022\u82dc\u84ff\u56ed\n| native_name_lang = zh-Hans\n| symbol_location  = nanjing\n| symbol           = metro\n| symbol_location2 = \n| symbol2          = \n| symbol_location3 = \n| symbol3          = \n| symbol_location4 = \n| symbol4          = \n| image            = Muxuyuan Station.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = The [[Line 2, Nanjing Metro|Line 2]] platform of Muxuyuan station.\n| mlanguage        = {{Infobox Chinese/Chinese|order=st |s=\u660e\u5b5d\u9675\u2022\u82dc\u84ff\u56ed\u7ad9 |t=\u660e\u5b5d\u9675\u2022\u82dc\u84ff\u5712\u7ad9 |p=M\u00edng Xi\u00e0o L\u00edng\u2022M\u00f9xuyu\u00e1n Zh\u00e0n}}\n| other_name       = Ming Xiaoling Mausoleum\n| borough          = [[Xuanwu District, Nanjing|Xuanwu District]], [[Nanjing]], [[Jiangsu]]\n| country          = China\n| coordinates      = \n| operator         = \n| line             = {{rail color box|system=NJM|line=2|inline=yes}}\n| platforms        =  <!-- Note that island platforms each count as *two* platforms and not one \u2013 check the station layout; remove this comment afterwards -->\n| connections      = \n| structure        = Underground\n| disabled         = \n| code             = \n| opened           = {{start date|2010|5|28|df=yes}}\n| closed           = \n| former           = \n| passengers       = \n| pass_year        = \n| services         = {{s-rail|title=NJM}}\n{{s-line|system=NJM|line=2|previous=Minggugong|next=Xiamafang}}\n}}\n'''Muxuyuan ([[Ming Xiaoling Mausoleum]]) Station''' is a [[railway station]] on [[Line 2, Nanjing Metro|Line 2]] of [[Nanjing Metro]]. It started operations on 28 May 2010 along with the rest of Line 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njmetro.com.cn/about_01_08show.aspx?Id=131 |script-title=zh:\u5927\u4e8b\u8bb0 |publisher=Nanjing Metro |quote={{lang|zh-hans|5\u670828\u65e5 \u5357\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u4e8c\u53f7\u7ebf\u53ca\u4e00\u53f7\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u7ebf\u5efa\u6210\u901a\u8f66\uff0c\u8fd0\u8425\u91cc\u7a0b\u8dc3\u5c45\u5168\u56fd\u7b2c\u56db\uff0c\u521d\u73b0\u7f51\u7edc\u5316\u8fd0\u8425\u683c\u5c40}} |accessdate=2018-07-24 }}</ref><ref name=\"sina line1+2+10\">{{citeweb|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/c/2010-05-23/032220327522.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303210702/http://news.sina.com.cn/c/2010-05-23/032220327522.shtml|archivedate=March 3, 2016|script-title=zh:\u5357\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u4e8c\u53f7\u7ebf\u8f7d\u4eba\u6a21\u62df\u8fd0\u8425|trans-title=Nanjing Metro Line 2 Undergoes Trial Runs|language=Chinese|work=Yantse Evening News|date=May 23, 2010|accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nIt has a length of {{convert|199.68|m|abbr=on}}, a width of {{convert|20.8|m|abbr=on}}, a height of {{convert|14.46|m|abbr=on}}, and it covers an area of {{convert|11015|m2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Structure\">{{cite web|url=http://www.njmetro.com.cn/service_05.aspx |script-title=zh:\u8f66\u7ad9\u7b80\u4ecb |publisher=Nanjing Metro |quote=Find the station name and direct your mouse pointer to it, wait until the icon turns into a darker color, and click. |accessdate=2018-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Decorations==\nSince Line 2 of the Nanjing Metro is centered on Chinese traditional festivals, the theme of this station's decorations is the [[Qixi Festival]].<ref name=\"Line 2 station themes\">{{cite web|url=http://js.xhby.net/system/2010/04/21/010732431.shtml |script-title=zh:\u8282\u65e5\u6587\u5316\u5899\u73b0\u8eab\u5730\u94c1\u4e8c\u53f7\u7ebf|publisher=\u5357\u4eac\u6668\u62a5 [Nanjing Morning News] |quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u636e\u4ecb\u7ecd\uff0c\u5143\u901a\u7ad9\u8bbe\u7684\u662f\u201c\u5143\u5bb5\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u5174\u9686\u5927\u8857\u7ad9\u201c\u56fd\u5e86\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u96c6\u5e86\u95e8\u5927\u8857\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u4e2d\u79cb\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u8336\u4ead\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u6e05\u660e\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u83ab\u6101\u6e56\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u7aef\u5348\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u5927\u884c\u5bab\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u6625\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u660e\u6545\u5bab\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u91cd\u9633\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u82dc\u84ff\u56ed\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u4e03\u5915\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u949f\u7075\u8857\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u51ac\u81f3\u201d\uff0c\u9a6c\u7fa4\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u5143\u65e6\u201d\uff0c\u5357\u5927\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u56fd\u9645\u52b3\u52a8\u8282\u201d\u3002}} |date=2010-04-21}}</ref> At {{convert|700|m2|abbr=on}}, It features the largest painting area of any Line 2 station,<ref name=\"Line 2 station themes\"/> if not the entire Nanjing Metro system. Several traditional romance stories can be seen if one looks up at the ceiling, such as [[The Cowherd and the Weaver Girl|Niulang and Zhin\u00fc]], [[Houyi]] and [[Chang'e]] and so on.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nj-dt.com/index2_8.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-06-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106014733/http://www.nj-dt.com/index2_8.asp |archivedate=6 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, the station became the second in the Nanjing Metro system, after {{NJM stations|Xuezelu}}, to install a set of \"musical stairs\" leading up from the station platform.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u97f3\u4e50\u697c\u68af\u201c\u4eae\u76f8\u201d\u5730\u94c1\u82dc\u84ff\u56ed\u7ad9|url=http://jsnews2.jschina.com.cn/system/2013/04/23/016994346.shtml|date=2013-04-23|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u6c5f\u82cf\u7f51}}</ref> The stairs, christened \"music stairs\" ({{lang|zh-hans|\u97f3\u4e50\u697c\u68af}}), were intended to play chords from the ''[[Butterfly Lovers' Violin Concerto]]'' whenever passengers would use the stairs. However, repeated wear and tear on the steps has caused loss of this unique functionality.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u7ea2\u697c\u4e3b\u9898\u5899\u3001\u97f3\u4e50\u697c\u68af\u906d\u7834\u635f \u5357\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u5f88\u201c\u53d7\u4f24\u201d(\u56fe)|url=http://news.longhoo.net/2015-04/08/content_11469987.htm|publisher=\u9f99\u864e\u7f51|date=2015-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:201704 Concourse and Platform of Muxuyuan Station.jpg|Concourse and platform area\nFile:Zhinu, ceiling of Muxuyuan Station, Nanjing metro.jpg|Painting of Zhin\u00fc on the ceiling\nFile:201704 Music Stair on the platform of Muxuyuan Station.jpg|\"Music stair\" leading up from the platform\n</gallery>\n\n{{multiple image|align=center|width=700|direction=vertical\n|image2=CeilingPaintingOf MUXUYUAN StationOfNanjingMetro.JPG|caption2=Another set of ceiling paintings on the tale of Niulang and Zhin\u00fc\n}}\n\n==Around the station==\n* [[Ming Xiaoling Mausoleum]]\n* [[Nanjing Botanical Garden, Memorial Sun Yat-Sen]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.nj-dt.com/index2_14.asp |script-title=zh:\u6362\u4e58\u8def\u7ebf |publisher=Nanjing Metro}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106014733/http://www.nj-dt.com/index2_8.asp |script-title=zh:\u5357\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u7ebf\u8def |publisher=Nanjing Metro}}\n\n{{Nanjing Metro/stations\n|line2=yes\n}}\n\n{{coord|32|02|25|N|118|50|06|E|region:CN-32_type:railwaystation_source:kolossus-zhwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Nanjing Metro stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2010]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nanjing Metro station}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name             = Muxuyuan\n| native_name      = \u660e\u5b5d\u9675\u2022\u82dc\u84ff\u56ed\n| native_name_lang = zh-Hans\n| symbol_location  = nanjing\n| symbol           = metro\n| symbol_location2 = \n| symbol2          = \n| symbol_location3 = \n| symbol3          = \n| symbol_location4 = \n| symbol4          = \n| image            = Muxuyuan Station.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = The [[Line 2, Nanjing Metro|Line 2]] platform of Muxuyuan station.\n| mlanguage        = {{Infobox Chinese/Chinese|order=st |s=\u660e\u5b5d\u9675\u2022\u82dc\u84ff\u56ed\u7ad9 |t=\u660e\u5b5d\u9675\u2022\u82dc\u84ff\u5712\u7ad9 |p=M\u00edng Xi\u00e0o L\u00edng\u2022M\u00f9xuyu\u00e1n Zh\u00e0n}}\n| other_name       = Ming Xiaoling Mausoleum\n| borough          = [[Xuanwu District, Nanjing|Xuanwu District]], [[Nanjing]], [[Jiangsu]]\n| country          = China\n| coordinates      = \n| operator         = \n| line             = {{rail color box|system=NJM|line=2|inline=yes}}\n| platforms        =  <!-- Note that island platforms each count as *two* platforms and not one \u2013 check the station layout; remove this comment afterwards -->\n| connections      = \n| structure        = Underground\n| disabled         = \n| code             = \n| opened           = {{start date|2010|5|28|df=yes}}\n| closed           = \n| former           = \n| passengers       = \n| pass_year        = \n| services         = {{s-rail|title=NJM}}\n{{s-line|system=NJM|line=2|previous=Minggugong|next=Xiamafang}}\n}}\n'''Muxuyuan ([[Ming Xiaoling Mausoleum]]) Station''' is a [[railway station]] on [[Line 2, Nanjing Metro|Line 2]] of [[Nanjing Metro]]. It started operations on 28 May 2010 along with the rest of Line 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njmetro.com.cn/about_01_08show.aspx?Id=131 |script-title=zh:\u5927\u4e8b\u8bb0 |publisher=Nanjing Metro |quote={{lang|zh-hans|5\u670828\u65e5 \u5357\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u4e8c\u53f7\u7ebf\u53ca\u4e00\u53f7\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u7ebf\u5efa\u6210\u901a\u8f66\uff0c\u8fd0\u8425\u91cc\u7a0b\u8dc3\u5c45\u5168\u56fd\u7b2c\u56db\uff0c\u521d\u73b0\u7f51\u7edc\u5316\u8fd0\u8425\u683c\u5c40}} |accessdate=2018-07-24 }}</ref><ref name=\"sina line1+2+10\">{{citeweb|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/c/2010-05-23/032220327522.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303210702/http://news.sina.com.cn/c/2010-05-23/032220327522.shtml|archivedate=March 3, 2016|script-title=zh:\u5357\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u4e8c\u53f7\u7ebf\u8f7d\u4eba\u6a21\u62df\u8fd0\u8425|trans-title=Nanjing Metro Line 2 Undergoes Trial Runs|language=Chinese|work=Yantse Evening News|date=May 23, 2010|accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nIt has a length of {{convert|199.68|m|abbr=on}}, a width of {{convert|20.8|m|abbr=on}}, a height of {{convert|14.46|m|abbr=on}}, and it covers an area of {{convert|11015|m2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Structure\">{{cite web|url=http://www.njmetro.com.cn/service_05.aspx |script-title=zh:\u8f66\u7ad9\u7b80\u4ecb |publisher=Nanjing Metro |quote=Find the station name and direct your mouse pointer to it, wait until the icon turns into a darker color, and click. |accessdate=2018-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Decorations==\nSince Line 2 of the Nanjing Metro is centered on Chinese traditional festivals, the theme of this station's decorations is the [[Qixi Festival]].<ref name=\"Line 2 station themes\">{{cite web|url=http://js.xhby.net/system/2010/04/21/010732431.shtml |script-title=zh:\u8282\u65e5\u6587\u5316\u5899\u73b0\u8eab\u5730\u94c1\u4e8c\u53f7\u7ebf|publisher=\u5357\u4eac\u6668\u62a5 [Nanjing Morning News] |quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u636e\u4ecb\u7ecd\uff0c\u5143\u901a\u7ad9\u8bbe\u7684\u662f\u201c\u5143\u5bb5\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u5174\u9686\u5927\u8857\u7ad9\u201c\u56fd\u5e86\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u96c6\u5e86\u95e8\u5927\u8857\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u4e2d\u79cb\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u8336\u4ead\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u6e05\u660e\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u83ab\u6101\u6e56\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u7aef\u5348\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u5927\u884c\u5bab\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u6625\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u660e\u6545\u5bab\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u91cd\u9633\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u82dc\u84ff\u56ed\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u4e03\u5915\u8282\u201d\uff0c\u949f\u7075\u8857\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u51ac\u81f3\u201d\uff0c\u9a6c\u7fa4\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u5143\u65e6\u201d\uff0c\u5357\u5927\u7ad9\u7684\u201c\u56fd\u9645\u52b3\u52a8\u8282\u201d\u3002}} |date=2010-04-21}}</ref> At {{convert|700|m2|abbr=on}}, It features the largest painting area of any Line 2 station,<ref name=\"Line 2 station themes\"/> if not the entire Nanjing Metro system. Several traditional romance stories can be seen if one looks up at the ceiling, such as [[The Cowherd and the Weaver Girl|Niulang and Zhin\u00fc]], [[Houyi]] and [[Chang'e]] and so on.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nj-dt.com/index2_8.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-06-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106014733/http://www.nj-dt.com/index2_8.asp |archivedate=6 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, the station became the second in the Nanjing Metro system, after {{NJM stations|Xuezelu}}, to install a set of \"musical stairs\" leading up from the station platform.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u97f3\u4e50\u697c\u68af\u201c\u4eae\u76f8\u201d\u5730\u94c1\u82dc\u84ff\u56ed\u7ad9|url=http://jsnews2.jschina.com.cn/system/2013/04/23/016994346.shtml|date=2013-04-23|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u6c5f\u82cf\u7f51}}</ref> The stairs, christened \"music stairs\" ({{lang|zh-hans|\u97f3\u4e50\u697c\u68af}}), were intended to play chords from the ''[[Butterfly Lovers' Violin Concerto]]'' whenever passengers would use the stairs. However, repeated wear and tear on the steps has caused loss of this unique functionality.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u7ea2\u697c\u4e3b\u9898\u5899\u3001\u97f3\u4e50\u697c\u68af\u906d\u7834\u635f \u5357\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u5f88\u201c\u53d7\u4f24\u201d(\u56fe)|url=http://news.longhoo.net/2015-04/08/content_11469987.htm|publisher=\u9f99\u864e\u7f51|date=2015-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:201704 Concourse and Platform of Muxuyuan Station.jpg|Concourse and platform area\nFile:Zhinu, ceiling of Muxuyuan Station, Nanjing metro.jpg|Painting of Zhin\u00fc on the ceiling\nFile:201704 Music Stair on the platform of Muxuyuan Station.jpg|\"Music stair\" leading up from the platform\n</gallery>\n\n{{multiple image|align=center|width=700|direction=vertical\n|image2=CeilingPaintingOf MUXUYUAN StationOfNanjingMetro.JPG|caption2=Another set of ceiling paintings on the tale of Niulang and Zhin\u00fc\n}}\n\n==Around the station==\n* [[Ming Xiaoling Mausoleum]]\n* [[Nanjing Botanical Garden, Memorial Sun Yat-Sen]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.nj-dt.com/index2_14.asp |script-title=zh:\u6362\u4e58\u8def\u7ebf |publisher=Nanjing Metro}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106014733/http://www.nj-dt.com/index2_8.asp |script-title=zh:\u5357\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u7ebf\u8def |publisher=Nanjing Metro}}\n\n{{Nanjing Metro/stations\n|line2=yes\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{coord|32|02|25|N|118|50|06|E|region:CN-32_type:railwaystation_source:kolossus-zhwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Nanjing Metro stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2010]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in China]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:DATEUNIFY (audit)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muxuyuan_station"}
{"title_page": "Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230", "text_new": "{{About|the motet|a similarly titled cantata|Lobet den Herrn, alle seine Heerscharen, BWV Anh. 5}}\n{{Listen\n| filename     = Lobet den herrn BWV 230 by J.S. Bach St. Andrew's Choir Easter 2012.ogg\n| title        = BWV 230\n| description  = Lobet den Herrn BWV 230 by J.S. Bach St. Andrew's Choir Easter 2012\n| filename2    = Johann Sebastian Bach - BWV 230 - Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden (Psalm 117).mid\n| title2       = Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden (BWV 230)\n| description2 = Keyboard only.\n}}\n'''''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden''''' (''Praise the Lord, all ye nations''),<ref name=\"Emmanuel\">{{cite web | url=http://emmanuelmusic.org/notes_translations/translations_motets/t_bwv230.htm | title=Motet Translations | publisher=[[Emmanuel Music]] | accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> '''[[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis|BWV]] 230''', is a [[Motets (Bach)|motet]] by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. It draws its text from [[Psalm 117]] [[s:Bible (King James)/Psalms#117:1|Verses 1-2]].\n\nIt is not known when the work was composed. Some scholars have questioned the attribution to Bach.<ref name=\"ml\">{{cite web | url= https://www.jstor.org/stable/731829| title=Bach's Setting of Psalm CXVII (BWV.230) | publisher=OUP | work=[[Music & Letters]]. Vol. 52, No. 1 | date=January 1971 | author=Leavis, Ralph}}  Accessed via JSTOR (subscription required)</ref>{{sfn|Wolf|2002|p=}} \nIn the twentieth century the authoritative [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis]] catalogue included it in a set of motets (BWV 225\u2013231). In retrospect, the BWV numbering seems somewhat arbitrary as a grouping of the Bach motets: recent scholarship includes more works among the motets. However, ''Lobet den Herrn'' has often been recorded with others from BWV 225-229. It is the only one of the set to be scored for four voices. It is also unusual in that (lightly scored) instrumental accompaniment is specified.<ref name=\"ml\" />\n\n== Publication ==\n=== 19th century editions ===\nIt was first published in 1821. The publisher claimed to have had access to an autograph score. \n=== 20th century editions ===\nIt was included in the [[New Bach Edition]] in 1965. \n=== 21st century editions ===\nIt was published by [[Carus-Verlag]] as one of seven motets edited by [[Uwe Wolf (musicologist)|Uwe Wolf]]. The editor acknowledges some doubt about the authenticity of the work, explaining that \"in contrast to the 'classical' number of six works we have published seven compositions in this volume of motets: five undoubtedly authentic works by Johann Sebastian Bach and two whose authenticity is less certain\".{{sfn|Wolf|2002|p=}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite web\n| last = \n| first = \n| authorlink = \n| editor-last = Wolf\n| editor-first = Uwe\n| editor-link = Uwe Wolf (musicologist)\n| url = https://www.carusmedia.com/images-intern/medien/30/3122410/3122410x.pdf\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach / Motetten / Motets\n| website = [[Carus-Verlag]]\n| date = 2002\n| page = V\n| accessdate = 24 March 2020\n| ref = harv\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231.htm Information on the work on www.bach-cantatas.com]\n*{{IMSLP2|work=Lobet_den_Herrn,_alle_Heiden,_BWV_230_%28Bach,_Johann_Sebastian%29|cname=Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden}}\n*[http://www.emmanuelmusic.org/notes_translations/translations_motets/t_bwv230.htm J.S. Bach: Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230] English and German texts at [[Emmanuel Music]]\n\n{{Bach motets}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden'', BWV 230}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Motets by Johann Sebastian Bach]]\n[[Category:Psalm-related compositions by Johann Sebastian Bach]]\n\n\n{{Classical-composition-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the motet|a similarly titled cantata|Lobet den Herrn, alle seine Heerscharen, BWV Anh. 5}}\n{{Listen\n| filename     = Lobet den herrn BWV 230 by J.S. Bach St. Andrew's Choir Easter 2012.ogg\n| title        = BWV 230\n| description  = Lobet den Herrn BWV 230 by J.S. Bach St. Andrew's Choir Easter 2012\n| filename2    = Johann Sebastian Bach - BWV 230 - Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden (Psalm 117).mid\n| title2       = Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden (BWV 230)\n| description2 = Keyboard only.\n}}\n'''''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden''''' (''Praise the Lord, all ye nations''),<ref name=\"Emmanuel\">{{cite web | url=http://emmanuelmusic.org/notes_translations/translations_motets/t_bwv230.htm | title=Motet Translations | publisher=[[Emmanuel Music]] | accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> '''[[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis|BWV]] 230''', is a [[Motets (Bach)|motet]] by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. It draws its text from [[Psalm 117]] [[s:Bible (King James)/Psalms#117:1|Verses 1-2]].\n\nIt is not known when the work was composed. Some scholars have questioned the attribution to Bach.<ref name=\"ml\">{{cite web | url= https://www.jstor.org/stable/731829| title=Bach's Setting of Psalm CXVII (BWV.230) | publisher=OUP | work=[[Music & Letters]]. Vol. 52, No. 1 | date=January 1971 | author=Leavis, Ralph}}  Accessed via JSTOR (susbscription required)</ref> In the twentieth century the authoritative [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis]] catalogue included it in a set of motets (BWV 225\u2013231). In retrospect, the BWV numbering seems somewhat arbitrary as a grouping of the Bach motets: recent scholarship includes more works among the motets. However, ''Lobet den Herrn'' has often been recorded with others from BWV 225-229. It is the only one of the set to be scored for four voices. It is also unusual in that (lightly scored) instrumental accompaniment is specified.<ref name=\"ml\" />\n\n== Publication ==\n=== 19th century editions ===\nIt was first published in 1821. The publisher claimed to have had access to an autograph score. \n=== 20th century editions ===\nIt was included in the [[New Bach Edition]] in 1965. \n=== 21st century editions ===\nIt was published by [[Carus-Verlag]] as one of seven motets edited by [[Uwe Wolf (musicologist)|Uwe Wolf]]. The editor acknowledges some doubt about the authenticity of the work, explaining that \"in contrast to the 'classical' number of six works we have published seven compositions in this volume of motets: five undoubtedly authentic works by Johann Sebastian Bach and two whose authenticity is less certain\".{{sfn|Wolf|2002|p=}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite web\n| last = \n| first = \n| authorlink = \n| editor-last = Wolf\n| editor-first = Uwe\n| editor-link = Uwe Wolf (musicologist)\n| url = https://www.carusmedia.com/images-intern/medien/30/3122410/3122410x.pdf\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach / Motetten / Motets\n| website = [[Carus-Verlag]]\n| date = 2002\n| page = V\n| accessdate = 24 March 2020\n| ref = harv\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231.htm Information on the work on www.bach-cantatas.com]\n*{{IMSLP2|work=Lobet_den_Herrn,_alle_Heiden,_BWV_230_%28Bach,_Johann_Sebastian%29|cname=Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden}}\n*[http://www.emmanuelmusic.org/notes_translations/translations_motets/t_bwv230.htm J.S. Bach: Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230] English and German texts at [[Emmanuel Music]]\n\n{{Bach motets}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden'', BWV 230}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Motets by Johann Sebastian Bach]]\n[[Category:Psalm-related compositions by Johann Sebastian Bach]]\n\n\n{{Classical-composition-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Thoughtfortheday", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lobet_den_Herrn,_alle_Heiden,_BWV_230"}
